# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: alaska-day
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:alaska-day/420-cannabis-culture] Five high school students in San Rafael, California, coined the term as part of their 1971 search for an abandoned cannabis crop, based on a treasure map made by the grower.
[src:alaska-day/420-cannabis-culture] The Waldos referred to this plan with the phrase "4:20 Louis".
[src:alaska-day/420-cannabis-culture] After several failed attempts to find the crop, the group eventually shortened their phrase to "4:20", which ultimately evolved into a code-word the teens used to refer to consuming cannabis.
[src:alaska-day/420-cannabis-culture] Steven Hager of *High Times* popularized the story of the Waldos.
[src:alaska-day/420-cannabis-culture] The first *High Times* mention of 4:20 smoking and a 4/20 holiday appeared in May 1991 and erroneously attributed the origin of the term to a police code; this and other spurious origin stories became common.
[src:alaska-day/420-cannabis-culture] The connection to the Waldos appeared in December 1998.
[src:alaska-day/420-cannabis-culture] Hager attributed the early spread of the phrase to Grateful Dead followers—after "Waldo" Reddix became a roadie for the Grateful Dead bassist, Phil Lesh—and called for 4:20 p.m. to be the socially accepted time of the day to consume cannabis.
[src:alaska-day/420-cannabis-culture] Another San Rafael group led by Brad "The Bebe" Bann claims to have originated the term before the Waldos.
[src:alaska-day/420-cannabis-culture] April 20 has become an international counterculture holiday based on the celebration and consumption of cannabis, as well as "cannabis culture, protest and advocacy".
[src:alaska-day/420-cannabis-culture] Events typically advocate for cannabis liberalization and legalization.
[src:alaska-day/420-cannabis-culture] Vivian McPeak, a founder of Seattle's Hempfest, states that 4/20 is "half celebration and half call to action".
[src:alaska-day/420-cannabis-culture] Paul Birch calls it a global movement and suggests that one cannot stop events like these.
[src:alaska-day/420-cannabis-culture] Many marijuana users protest in civil disobedience by gathering in public to smoke at 4:20 p.m.
[src:alaska-day/420-cannabis-culture] In the United Kingdom, events have been held in Hyde Park in London.
[src:alaska-day/420-cannabis-culture] Events have also been held in Brighton, Bristol, Durham, Glasgow, Leeds, and Plymouth.
[src:alaska-day/420-cannabis-culture] The Teesside Cannabis Club also holds an annual event.
[src:alaska-day/420-cannabis-culture] In Northern Cyprus, known for strict drug laws and intolerance to cannabis consumption, the first 420 event was held in the capital city Lefkoşa in 2015.
[src:alaska-day/420-cannabis-culture] On April 20, 2017, a small group of protesters carried out an event near the parliament building and made a public statement, demanding the legalization of cannabis sale, consumption, and production with state regulations.
[src:alaska-day/420-cannabis-culture] Events have been held in Dunedin, New Zealand, at the University of Otago.
[src:alaska-day/420-cannabis-culture] Despite two studies reporting a supposed increase in the risk of fatal motor vehicle crashes on April 20, further investigation and analysis found the evidence did not support such claims.
[src:alaska-day/420-cannabis-culture] In the US, signs bearing the number 420 have been frequently stolen.
[src:alaska-day/420-cannabis-culture] In Colorado, the Colorado Department of Transportation replaced the Mile Marker 420 sign on I-70 east of Denver with one reading 419.99 in an attempt to stop the thievery.
[src:alaska-day/420-cannabis-culture] The Idaho Department of Transportation (ITD) replaced the mile marker 420 sign on U.S.
[src:alaska-day/420-cannabis-culture] Highway 95, just south of Coeur d'Alene, with mile marker 419.9.
[src:alaska-day/420-cannabis-culture] The Washington State Department of Transportation implemented similar measures, but only replaced one of the two 420 signs in the state, with the remaining one being subsequently stolen.
[src:alaska-day/420-cannabis-culture] According to *The Washington Post*, there are eleven 420 mile markers in the US, after three replacements and one stolen and not replaced.
[src:alaska-day/420-cannabis-culture] In Goodhue County, Minnesota, officials have changed "420 St" street signs to "42x St".
[src:alaska-day/420-cannabis-culture] Route 89, the only 420 marker in the state of Utah, is frequently stolen.
[src:alaska-day/420-cannabis-culture] In 2003, California Senate Bill 420 was introduced to regulate medical marijuana use.
[src:alaska-day/420-cannabis-culture] An unsuccessful 2010 bill to legalize cannabis in Guam was called Bill 420.
[src:alaska-day/420-cannabis-culture] A North Dakota bill to legalize cannabis was HB 1420, introduced in January 2021.
[src:alaska-day/420-cannabis-culture] The Marijuana Freedom and Opportunity Act (which if enacted would decriminalize and deschedule cannabis in the United States) was announced by Senator and Senate Minority Leader Chuck Schumer (D-New York) on April 20, 2018.
[src:alaska-day/420-cannabis-culture] 420 was introduced into the 116th Congress by Representative Earl Blumenauer (D-Oregon), named the Regulate Marijuana Like Alcohol Act, which is designed to remove cannabis from the Controlled Substances Act and return regulation to the states.
[src:alaska-day/420-cannabis-culture] The State of Colorado auctioned off several cannabis-themed personalized license plates in 2021, with the bidding to be closed on April 20 (4/20).
[src:alaska-day/420-cannabis-culture] The highest bid shortly before the auction closed was over $6,500 for "ISIT420".
[src:alaska-day/420-cannabis-culture] Following the success of Washington, D.C.'s Initiative 71 to legalize cannabis in 2014, Mayor Muriel Bowser granted license plate number 420 to the campaign's leader, Adam Eidinger.
[src:alaska-day/420-cannabis-culture] The U.S. federal government and some localities conduct Anti-420 public service announcement campaigns.
[src:alaska-day/420-cannabis-culture] Several books about cannabis have "420" in the title; examples include the cannabis cookbooks *The 420 Cannabis Cookbook*, published by Simon & Schuster, and *The 420 Gourmet* published in 2016 by HarperCollins.
[src:alaska-day/420-cannabis-culture] Several American restaurant chains have offered "420" themed promotions to coincide with April 20.
[src:alaska-day/420-cannabis-culture] They included well known national chains Wingstop, KFC, and Taco Bell, as well as smaller entities like Voodoo Donut.
[src:alaska-day/420-cannabis-culture] Tesla CEO Elon Musk tweeted in 2018 about taking his company private at $420 a share.
[src:alaska-day/420-cannabis-culture] Musk testified during a trial that any associations with cannabis were coincidental; however, in the SEC filing, he admitted that he had recently discovered the number's importance within the cannabis culture and thought his girlfriend would find it funny.
[src:alaska-day/420-cannabis-culture] Musk purchased Twitter in 2022 at $54.20 per share and the financing documents were signed on April 20, acknowledging the reference to marijuana culture both in the last three digits of the price and in the date.
[src:alaska-day/420-cannabis-culture] Musk continued making 420 references in June 2025 when Tesla Robotaxi service was launched in Austin, Texas where a flat fee of $4.20 was introduced, regardless of the distance travelled.
[src:alaska-day/advent-sunday] On the First Sunday of Advent, Christians start lighting the candles of their Advent wreaths, and praying their Advent daily devotional.
[src:alaska-day/advent-sunday] The faithful may also erect a Chrismon tree or light a Christingle.
[src:alaska-day/advent-sunday] They may also prepare for Christmas in other ways, such as setting up Christmas decorations, a custom that is sometimes done liturgically through a hanging of the greens ceremony.
[src:alaska-day/advent-sunday] In Lutheran, Anglican, and Methodist churches the celebrant wears violet-coloured or blue vestments on this day, and the first violet or blue Advent candle is lit in the worship service.
[src:alaska-day/advent-sunday] In the Church of Sweden, a Lutheran national Church, the liturgical colour is specifically white: the motivation is that the day is a joyful feast (the colour is changed to blue, the traditional colour for Advent in Scandinavia, or—if the church does not possess blue vestments—violet, after 6 p.m.).
[src:alaska-day/advent-sunday] Zechariah 9:9–10 and Matthew 21:1–9 are always read in the service, and the symbolism of the day is that Christ enters the church.
[src:alaska-day/advent-sunday] Likewise, in the Roman Rite of the Catholic Church, Advent also "begins with First Vespers (Evening Prayer I) of the Sunday that falls on or closest to 30 November and it ends before First Vespers (Evening Prayer I) of Christmas".
[src:alaska-day/advent-sunday] The colour violet or purple is used in Advent, but where it is the practice the colour rose may be used on Gaudete Sunday (Third Sunday of Advent).
[src:alaska-day/advent-sunday] Advent Sunday is the fourth Sunday before Christmas Day, whether celebrated according to the Gregorian or Julian calendar.
[src:alaska-day/advent-sunday] It can fall on any date between 27 November and 3 December.
[src:alaska-day/advent-sunday] When Christmas Day is a Monday, Advent Sunday will fall on its latest possible date.
[src:alaska-day/advent-sunday] For most Christians, Advent Sunday is the Sunday nearest to St.
[src:alaska-day/advent-sunday] It is possible to compute the date of Advent Sunday by adding three days to the date of the last Thursday of November; it can also be computed as the Sunday before the first Thursday of December.
[src:alaska-day/advent-sunday] In the Ambrosian Rite and the Mozarabic Rite, the First Sunday in Advent comes two weeks earlier than in the Roman, being on the Sunday after St.
[src:alaska-day/advent-sunday] Martin's Day (11 November), six weeks before Christmas.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-day] On March 30, 1867, the United States purchased Alaska from the Russian Empire for the sum of $7.2 million, equivalent to $132 million in 2024.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-day] It was not until October of that year that the commissioners arrived in Sitka and the formal transfer was arranged.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-day] The formal flag-raising took place at Fort Sitka on October 18, 1867.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-day] The original ceremony included 250 United States Army troops, who marched to the governor's house at "Castle Hill".
[src:alaska-day/alaska-day] There, the American soldiers raised the American flag, and the Russian flag was lowered.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-day] The official account of the affair as presented by General Lovell Rousseau to Secretary of State William H.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-day] The transfer ceremony occurred on October 18, 1867, according to the Gregorian calendar used by the United States.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-day] However, Russia still used the Julian calendar at that time, which was 12 days behind the Gregorian calendar in the 19th century.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-day] Therefore, the date in the Russian calendar was October 6 (Old Style), though some sources cite October 7 due to the 11-hour time difference between Sitka and St.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-day] Alaska's territorial legislature declared Alaska Day a holiday in 1917.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-day] It is a paid holiday for state employees.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-day] The annual celebration is held in Sitka, where schools release students early, many businesses close for the day, and events such as a parade and reenactment of the flag-raising are held.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-day] Alaska Day is distinct from Seward's Day, celebrated on the last Monday in March.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-day] Seward's Day commemorates the signing of the treaty for the Alaska Purchase in Washington, D.C. on March 30, 1867.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-day] Alaska Day is observed by some Alaska Native people with mixed feelings or protest, as they view the holiday as celebrating events that resulted in significant impacts to their communities and sovereignty.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-day] Native organizers have asserted that the land was not Russia's to sell, as Indigenous peoples had inhabited the territory for thousands of years; therefore, they consider the sale of the land to the U.S. without Native consent to be illegitimate.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-day] In recent years, some Alaska Native groups and community organizers have continued to hold events or discussions aimed at raising awareness of historical impacts, while local governments maintain October 18 as a legal holiday.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-day] Some Alaska Natives have characterized the events surrounding the transfer and subsequent treatment of Indigenous peoples as forms of cultural genocide.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-day] In response to these concerns, Peter Bradley, a former resident of Sitka, formally proposed a resolution calling for the renaming of Alaska Day to Reconciliation Day, seeking to acknowledge both the historical significance of the transfer and the perspectives of Alaska Native communities.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] The migration of Alaska Natives' ancestors into the Alaskan region occurred thousands of years ago in multiple waves.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] Some present-day groups descend from a later migration event whose descendants gradually settled across northern North America.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] The Alaska Native's ancestors are the ones who did not migrate further south or east.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] Genetic evidence indicates that these groups are not closely related to the Indigenous peoples of South America.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] Evidence from archaeology indicates that the ancestors of Alaska Natives migrated from Asia.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] Anthropologists have proposed that their journey to Alaska from Asia was made possible through the Bering land bridge or by traveling across the sea.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] Across the Arctic and the circumpolar north, the ancestors of Alaska Natives established a variety of Indigenous cultures that developed and changed over time.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] These cultures demonstrated considerable ingenuity in adapting to harsh climates and environments.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] Historically, the defining characteristic of Alaska Native groups has often been their languages, which belong to several major language families.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] Currently, Alaska Natives or Native Alaskans constitute more than 20% of Alaska's population.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] The vast majority of Alaska Natives are either Eskaleut or Na Dene.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] As of 2018, Alaska Natives constituted 15.4% of the overall Alaskan population.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] Earlier data from the Alaskan Natives Commission estimated approximately 86,000 Alaska Natives residing in Alaska in 1990, with an additional 17,000 living outside of the state.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] More recently, a 2013 study conducted by the Alaska Department of Labor and Workforce Development documented over 120,000 Alaska Native Individuals within Alaska.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] While a significant portion of the Alaska Native populations resides in smaller villages or remote regional hubs such as Nome, Dillingham, and Bethel, there has been a notable increase in the percentage living in urban areas.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] According to the 2010 census, 44% of Alaska Natives lived in urban areas, a rise from 38% recorded in the 2000 census.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] The pre-contact population of Alaska Natives, in year 1750, before first European settlement, is estimated as around 93,800 people.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] In 1870 the native population of Alaska was still estimated as 70,000 people.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] However, the census of 1880 found only 32,996 Native Alaskans.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] The population of Alaska Natives then further declined to 25,450 people in 1910 (of whom 25,328 lived in Alaska and 122 in the rest of the United States).
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] Since 1910 the population began rebounding, and it reached 168,826 people in year 2010.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] Of them 124,758 lived in Alaska and 44,068 in the rest of the United States.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] The modern history of Alaska Natives began in the eighteenth century with the initial contact between Alaskan First Nations and Russian explorers sailing from Siberia.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] Subsequently, in the nineteenth century, British and American traders, coming mostly from eastern settlements in North America, arrived in the region.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] In some areas of Alaska, the active presence of Christian missionaries did not occur until the twentieth century.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] Vitus Bering spotted Alaska during an expedition.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] Subsequently, in the 18th century, Alaska Natives encountered Russians, with the timing of this contact varying among different Native groups across Alaska.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] Arriving by ship from Siberia, in the mid-eighteenth century, Russians established trade with Alaska Natives, particularly in the Aleutian Islands.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] They founded settlements around their trading posts, which included Russian Orthodox missionaries.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] These missionaries were the first to translate Christian scripture into Native languages, such as Tlingit.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] The lasting impact of this period is evident in the 21st century with numerous Russian Orthodox Christian congregations in Alaska composed predominantly of Alaska Natives.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] The Sibero-Russian *promyshlenniki*, rather than engaging in hunting and harvesting marine life themselves, coerced the Aleuts into performing this labor, enserfing the Aleuts.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] As news for the fur trade spread, competition among Russian companies intensified.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] Catherine the Great, upon ascending to the throne in 1763, expressed goodwill towards the Aleuts and encouraged fair treatment.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] However, the increasing competition between trading companies, which eventually consolidated into larger and more powerful corporations, led to conflicts that worsened relations with the Indigenous populations.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] Over time, the situation became dire for the Aleuts and other Native Alaskan people affected by Russian contact.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] As the animal populations declined, the Aleuts, already dependent on the new barter economy driven by the fur trade with the Russians, faced increasing pressure to take greater risks in the dangerous waters of the North Pacific to hunt for more otter.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] The Shelikhov-Golikov Company, and later Russian-American Company developed as a monopoly, using skirmishes and systematic violence as tools for the colonial exploitation of the Indigenous peoples.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] When the Aleut revolted and won some victories, the Russians retaliated with deadly force, destroying their boats and hunting equipment, leaving them no means of survival.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] The most devastating impact on the Aleut population during the initial two generations of Russian contact (1741/1759-1781/1799 AD) was the introduction of new diseases from Eurasia.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] Approximately 80% of the Aleut population perished from these infectious diseases, to which they had no immunity, unlike Europeans among whom these diseases have been endemic for centuries.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] The Russian Tsarist government expanded into Indigenous territory in present-day Alaska for its own geopolitical reasons.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] It consumed natural resources of the territory during the trading years, and Russian Orthodoxy was evangelized.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] Their movement into these populated areas of Indigenous communities altered the demographic and natural landscape.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] Historians have suggested that the Russian-American Company exploited Indigenous peoples as a source of inexpensive labor.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] The Russian-American Company not only used Indigenous populations for labor during the fur trade, but also held some as hostages to acquire *iasak*.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] Iasak, a form of taxation imposed by the Russians, was a tribute in the form of otter pelts.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] It was a taxation method the Russians had previously found useful in their early encounter with Indigenous communities of Siberia during the Siberian fur trade.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] Beaver pelts were also customary to be given to fur traders upon first contact with various communities.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] The Russian-American Company used military force on Indigenous families, taking them hostage until male community members produced furs for them.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] Otter furs on Kodiak Island and Aleutian Islands enticed the Russians to start these taxations.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] Robbery and maltreatment in the form of corporal punishment and the withholding of food was also present upon the arrival of fur traders.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] Catherine the Great dissolved the giving of tribute in 1799, but her government initiated mandatory conscription of Indigenous men between the ages of 18 and 50 to become seal hunters strictly for the Russian American Company.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] This mandatory labor gave the Russian American Company an edge in competition with American and British fur traders.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] But the conscription separated men from their families and villages, thus altering and breaking down communities.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] With able-bodied men away on the hunt, villages were left with little protection as only women, children, and the elderly remained behind.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] In addition to changes that came with conscription, the spread of disease also altered the populations of Indigenous communities.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] Although records kept in the period were scarce, it has been said that 80% of the pre-contact population of the Aleut people were gone by 1800.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] The Alaska Native population was first recorded in the 1880 United States census, and it was estimated that the population had declined from 80,000 in 1741 to 33,000 due to disease.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] The population continued to decline until 1910 and it was not until 1947 that this number surpassed the 1880 figure.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] Relationships between Indigenous women and fur traders increased as Indigenous men were away from villages.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] This resulted in marriages and children that would come to be known as Creole peoples, children who were Indigenous and Russian.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] To reduce hostilities with Aleutian communities, it became policy for fur traders to enter into marriage with Indigenous women.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] The Creole population increased in the territory controlled by the Russian American Company.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] The growth of the Russian Orthodox Church was another important tactic in the colonization and conversion of Indigenous populations.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] Ioann Veniaminov, who later became Saint Innocent of Alaska, was an important missionary who carried out the Orthodox Church's agenda to Christianize Indigenous populations.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] The church encouraged Creole children to follow Russian Orthodox Christianity, while the Russian American Company provided them with an education.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] Many Orthodox missionaries, like Herman of Alaska, defended Natives from exploitation.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] Creole people were believed to have high levels of loyalty toward the Russian crown and Russian American Company.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] After completing their education, children were often sent to Russia, where they would study skills such as mapmaking, theology, and military intelligence.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] In the 1850s Russia lost much of its interest in Alaska.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] Alaska's abundance of natural resources, particularly gold, drew the interest of the United States.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] In 1867, the United States bought Alaska from Russia.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] This purchase happened without considering the opinions of the Native Alaskans, who were not regarded as citizens at the time.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] The land traditionally belonging to Alaska Natives was treated as "open land," allowing white settlers to claim it without providing any compensation or recognition to the Native people living there.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] The only educational opportunities available for Alaska Natives were in schools established by religious missionaries.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] Many white settlers failed to appreciate the complex and well-developed cultures that Alaska Natives had created to thrive in their challenging environment.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] Instead, they viewed them as inferior to European Americans, which aligned with white supremacist ideologies.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] The Klondike Gold Rush of 1896–1898 led to increased white settlement in Alaska and brought discriminatory practices against Indigenous peoples.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] American settlers imposed racial segregation and discriminatory laws similar to Jim Crow laws, which severely limited Alaska Natives' opportunities and cultural practices, effectively treating them as second-class citizens.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] This segregation manifested in various ways, including "whites only" signs that prevented natives from entering certain buildings.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] Educational discrimination was also prevalent.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] In an 1880 court case, a child was barred from attending school with Americans because his stepfather was native.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] Children of mixed heritage could only attend American schools if their families abandoned their native culture.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] Simultaneously, the U.S. government implemented policies to disrupt Alaska Native family structures.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] Federal records show that disrupting native family units was a deliberate part of Federal Indian policy aimed at assimilating Indigenous children.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] The Federal Indian Boarding School Initiative played a major role in creating intergenerational trauma by removing children from their native villages and placing them in off-reservation boarding schools alongside children from other tribes.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] This system created artificial communities of Indigenous children throughout the boarding school network, resulting in new Indigenous family structures depending on whether children returned to their native villages or settled elsewhere after completing their education.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] These policies prohibited Alaska Native children from speaking their native languages, wearing traditional clothing, associating with other natives, consuming traditional foods, or practicing their religions.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] The resulting family separation and cultural eradication caused significant intergenerational trauma.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] In 1912, the Alaska Native Brotherhood (ANB) was formed to help fight for citizenship rights.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] The Alaska Native Sisterhood (ANS) was created in 1915.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] Also in 1915, the Alaska Territorial legislature passed a law allowing Alaskan Natives the right to vote – but on the condition that they give up their cultural customs and traditions.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] The Indian Citizenship Act, passed in 1924, gave all Native Americans United States citizenship.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] ANB began to hold a great deal of political power in the 1920s.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] They protested the segregation of Alaska Natives in public areas and institutions, and also staged boycotts.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] Alberta Schenck (Inupiaq) staged a well-publicized protest against segregation in a movie theater in 1944.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] With the help of Elizabeth Peratrovich (Tlingit), the Alaska Equal Rights Act of 1945 was passed, ending segregation in Alaska.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] In 1942, during World War II, the United States forced evacuation of around nine hundred Aleuts from the Aleutian Islands.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] The idea was to remove the Aleuts from a potential combat zone during World War II for their own protection, but European Americans living in the same area were not forced to leave.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] The removal was handled so poorly that many Aleuts died after they were evacuated; the elderly and children had the highest mortality rates.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] Survivors returned to the islands to find their homes and possessions destroyed or looted.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] Civil rights activists such as Alberta Schenck Adams and Elizabeth Peratrovich protested discriminatory laws against Native Alaskans with what were effectively sit-ins and lobbying.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] The Alaska Equal Rights Act of 1945, the first anti-discrimination state law in the U.S., occurred as a result of these protests.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] It entitled all Alaskans to "full and equal enjoyment" of public areas and businesses, a ban on segregating signs, with discriminatory actions punishable by a $250 fine and up to 30 days in jail.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] Alaska became part of the United States in 1959 upon President Dwight D.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] Eisenhower recognizing Alaska as the 49th state.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] In 1971, with the support of Alaska Native leaders such as Emil Notti, Willie Hensley, and Byron Mallott, the U.S.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] Congress passed the Alaska Native Claims Settlement Act (ANCSA), which settled land and financial claims for lands and resources which the Alaska Natives had lost to European-Americans.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] It provided for the establishment of thirteen Alaska Native Regional Corporations to administer those claims.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] Similar to the separately defined status of the Canadian Inuit and First Nations in Canada, which are recognized as distinct peoples, in the United States, Alaska Natives or Native Alaskans are in some respects treated separately by the government from other Native Americans in the United States.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] This is in part related to their interactions with the U.S. government which occurred in a different historical period than its interactions during the period of westward expansion during the 19th century.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] Europeans and Americans did not have sustained encounters with the Alaska Natives until the late 19th and early 20th centuries when many were attracted to the region in gold rushes.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] The Alaska Natives were not allotted individual title in severalty to land under the Dawes Act of 1887 but were instead treated under the Alaska Native Allotment Act of 1906.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] The Allotment Act was repealed in 1971, following ANSCA, at which time reservations were ended.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] Another characteristic difference is that Alaska Native tribal governments do not have the power to collect taxes for business transacted on tribal land, per the United States Supreme Court decision in *Alaska v.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] Native Village of Venetie Tribal Government* (1998).
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] Except for the Tsimshian, Alaska Natives no longer hold reservations but do control some lands.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] Under the Marine Mammal Protection Act of 1972, Alaska Natives reserve the right to harvest whales and other marine mammals.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] Four Indigenous tribes in Alaska, the Shishmaref, Kivalina, Shaktoolik, and Newtok tribes, are among America's first climate refugees due to the impacts of sea ice melting and increased wildfires in their regions.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] Climate change has created extensive challenges for Alaska's native peoples, including increased vulnerability to disease, mental health issues, physical injuries, and food and water insecurity.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] According to the Environmental Protection Agency (EPA), coastal erosion from sea ice loss is displacing native communities.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] This melting also disrupts the migration patterns of animals that tribes depend on for sustenance, while eliminating traditional places to store harvested food.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] As permafrost thaws, existing infrastructure becomes unstable, leading to the collapse of Native villages.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] The Shishmaref, Kivalina, Shaktoolik, and Newtok tribes are situated on Alaska's west coast, where rising sea levels have intensified storm surges that erode their coastlines.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] These communities face forced migration because there is no suitable nearby land to relocate to, requiring them to abandon their traditional ways of life.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] Predictions indicate that a significant climate event could completely submerge these tribal lands in fewer than fifteen years.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] The changing climate has heightened safety risks for Alaska Natives.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] While thick ice layers were historically present year-round, warming temperatures have thinned the ice, increasing incidents of people falling through—a dangerous situation that leads to additional health concerns even for survivors.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] Water insecurity and deteriorating infrastructure have created sanitation problems, contributing to an increase in respiratory illnesses across Alaska.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] In 2005, pneumonia became the leading cause of hospitalizations in these regions.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] Many affected communities experience significant psychological stress due to both the immediate impacts of climate change and the complex challenges of relocation without established policies or pathways.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] Additional stress comes from infrastructure damage caused by thawing permafrost, with minimal regulatory guidance beyond the Alaskan government's recommendations to avoid building on permafrost or to use extra insulation on foundation walls.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] Food security has also deteriorated as animals relocate to more suitable habitats.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] Traditional underground ice cellars, once frozen year-round, now thaw during summer months, rendering food supplies inedible.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] Gathering of subsistence food continues to be an important economic and cultural activity for many Alaska Natives.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] In Utqiaġvik, Alaska, in 2005, more than 91 percent of the Iñupiat households which were interviewed still participated in the local subsistence economy, compared with the approximately 33 percent of non-Iñupiat households who used wild resources obtained from hunting, fishing, or gathering.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] But, unlike many tribes in the contiguous United States, Alaska Natives do not have treaties with the United States that protect their subsistence rights, except for the right to harvest whales and other marine mammals.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-natives] The Alaska Native Claims Settlement Act explicitly extinguished aboriginal hunting and fishing rights in the state of Alaska.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Alaska is the largest U.S. state by area—comprising more total area than the next three largest states of Texas, California, and Montana combined—and is the world's largest semi-exclave and seventh-largest subnational division.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] With a population of 740,133 in 2024, it is the third-least populous and most sparsely populated state in the U.S., but the most populous territory in North America located mostly north of the 60th parallel, with more than quadruple the combined populations of Northern Canada and Greenland.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Alaska contains the four largest cities in the United States by area, including the state capital, Juneau.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Alaska's most populous city is Anchorage, and approximately half the state's residents live within its metropolitan area.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Indigenous people have lived in Alaska for thousands of years, and it is widely believed that the region served as the entry point for the initial settlement of the Americas by way of the Bering land bridge.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] The Russian Empire was the first to actively colonize the area beginning in the 18th century, eventually establishing Russian America, which spanned most of the current state and promoted and maintained a native Alaskan Creole population.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] The expense and logistical difficulty of maintaining this distant possession prompted its sale to the U.S. in 1867 for US$7.2 million, equivalent to $166 million in 2025.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] The area went through several administrative changes before becoming organized as a territory on May 11, 1912.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] It was admitted as the 49th state of the U.S. on January 3, 1959.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] An abundance of natural resources—including commercial fishing and the extraction of natural gas and oil—has enabled Alaska to have one of the highest per capita incomes in the United States, despite having one of the smallest economies.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Armed Forces bases and tourism also contribute to the economy; more than half of Alaska is federally owned, containing national forests, national parks, and wildlife refuges.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] It is among the most irreligious states and one of the first to legalize recreational marijuana.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Alaska has the highest proportion of Native Americans of any U.S. state, at 22 percent.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] The name *Alaska* (Russian: Аля́ска, romanized: *Aljáska*) was introduced during the Russian colonial period when it was used to refer to the Alaska Peninsula.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] It was derived from an Aleut-language idiom, *alaxsxaq*, meaning 'the mainland' or, more literally, 'the object towards which the action of the sea is directed'.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Numerous Indigenous peoples occupied Alaska for thousands of years before the arrival of European peoples to the area.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Linguistic and DNA studies done here have provided evidence for the settlement of North America by way of the Bering land bridge.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] At the Upward Sun River site in the Tanana Valley in Alaska, remains of a six-week-old infant were found.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] The baby's DNA showed that she belonged to a population that was genetically separate from other Native groups present elsewhere in the New World at the end of the Pleistocene.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Ben Potter, the University of Alaska Fairbanks archaeologist who unearthed the remains at the Upward Sun River site in 2013, named this new group Ancient Beringian.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] The Tlingit people developed a society with a matrilineal kinship system of property inheritance and descent in what is present Southeast Alaska, along with parts of British Columbia and the Yukon.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Also in the Southeast were the Haida, now well known for their unique arts.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] The Tsimshian people came to Alaska from British Columbia in 1887, when President Grover Cleveland, and later the U.S.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Congress, granted them permission to settle on Annette Island and found the town of Metlakatla, Alaska.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] All three of these peoples, as well as other Indigenous peoples of the Pacific Northwest Coast, experienced smallpox outbreaks from the late 18th through the mid-19th century, with the most devastating epidemics occurring in the 1830s and 1860s, resulting in high fatalities and social disruption.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Some researchers believe the first Russian settlement in Alaska was established in the 17th century.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] According to this hypothesis, in 1648 several koches of Semyon Dezhnyov's expedition came ashore in Alaska by storm and founded this settlement.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] This hypothesis is based on the testimony of Chukchi geographer Nikolai Daurkin, who had visited Alaska in 1764–1765 and who had reported on a village on the Kheuveren River, populated by "bearded men" who "pray to the icons".
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Some modern researchers associate the Kheuveren with the Koyuk River.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] The first European vessel to reach Alaska is generally held to be the *St.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Gabriel* under the authority of the surveyor M.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Fyodorov on August 21, 1732, during an expedition of Siberian Cossack A.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Shestakov and Russian explorer Dmitry Pavlutsky (1729–1735).
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Another European contact with Alaska occurred in 1741, when Vitus Bering led an expedition for the Russian Navy aboard the *St.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] After his crew returned to Russia with sea otter pelts judged to be the finest fur in the world, small associations of fur traders began to sail from the shores of Siberia toward the Aleutian Islands.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] The first permanent European settlement was founded in 1784.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] From 1774 to 1800, Spain sent several expeditions to Alaska to assert its claim over the Pacific Northwest, which it considered part of New Spain, administered from Mexico City, Mexico.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] In 1789, a Spanish settlement and fort were built in Nootka Sound.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] These expeditions gave names to places such as Valdez, Bucareli Sound, and Cordova.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Later, the Russian-American Company carried out an expanded colonization program during the early-to-mid-19th century.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Sitka, renamed New Archangel from 1804 to 1867, on Baranof Island in the Alexander Archipelago in what is now Southeast Alaska, became the capital of Russian America.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] It remained the capital after the colony was transferred to the United States.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] The Russians never fully colonized Alaska, and the colony was never very profitable.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Evidence of Russian settlement in names and churches survives throughout southeastern Alaska.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Seward, the United States Secretary of State under President Andrew Johnson, negotiated the Alaska Purchase, referred to pejoratively as Seward's Folly, with the Russians for $7.2 million.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Russian emperor Alexander II also planned the sale.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] The purchase was made on March 30, 1867.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Six months later the commissioners arrived in Sitka and the formal transfer was arranged.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] The flag-raising took place at Fort Sitka on October 18, 1867.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] In the ceremony, 250 uniformed U.S. soldiers marched to the governor's house at "Castle Hill", where the Russian troops lowered the Russian flag and the U.S. flag was raised.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] This event is celebrated as Alaska Day, a legal holiday on October 18.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Alaska was loosely governed by the military initially and was administered as a district starting in 1884, with a governor appointed by the United States president.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] A federal district court was headquartered in Sitka.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] For most of Alaska's first decade under the United States flag, Sitka was the only community inhabited by American settlers.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] They organized "a provisional city government", which was Alaska's first municipal government, but not in a legal sense.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Legislation allowing Alaskan communities to legally incorporate as cities arrived in 1900, and home rule for cities was extremely limited or unavailable until statehood took effect in 1959.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Starting in the 1890s and stretching in some places to the early 1910s, gold rushes in Alaska and the nearby Yukon Territory brought thousands of miners and settlers to Alaska.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] In 1912, Alaska was incorporated as an organized territory.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Alaska's capital, which had been in Sitka until 1906, was moved north to Juneau.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Construction of the Alaska Governor's Mansion began that same year.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] European immigrants from Norway and Sweden also settled in southeast Alaska, where they entered the fishing and logging industries.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] During World War II, the Aleutian Islands Campaign focused on Attu, Agattu and Kiska, all of which were occupied by the Empire of Japan.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] During the Japanese occupation, an American civilian and two United States Navy personnel were killed at Attu and Kiska respectively, and almost 50 Aleut civilians and eight sailors were interned in Japan.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] About half of the Aleuts died during the period of internment.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Unalaska/Dutch Harbor and Adak became significant bases for the United States Army, United States Army Air Forces and United States Navy.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] The United States Lend-Lease program involved flying American warplanes through Canada to Fairbanks and then Nome.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Soviet pilots took possession of these aircraft, ferrying them to fight the German invasion of the Soviet Union.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] The construction of military bases contributed to the population growth of some Alaskan cities.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Statehood for Alaska was an important cause of James Wickersham early in his tenure as a congressional delegate.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Decades later, the statehood movement gained its first real momentum following a territorial referendum in 1946.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] The Alaska Statehood Committee and Alaska's Constitutional Convention soon followed.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Statehood supporters also found themselves fighting major battles against political foes, mostly in the U.S.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Alaska was officially proclaimed a state on January 3, 1959.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] On March 27, 1964, the Good Friday earthquake killed 133 people and destroyed several villages and portions of large coastal communities, mainly by the resultant tsunamis and landslides.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] It was the fourth-most-powerful earthquake in recorded history, with a moment magnitude of 9.2, more than a thousand times as powerful as the 1989 San Francisco earthquake.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] The time of day (5:36 pm), time of year (spring) and location of the epicenter were all cited as factors in potentially sparing thousands of lives, particularly in Anchorage.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] The Good Friday earthquake lasted 4 minutes and 38 seconds.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Six hundred miles (970 km) of fault ruptured at once and moved up to 60 ft (18 m), releasing about 500 years of stress buildup.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Soil liquefaction, fissures, landslides, and other ground failures caused major structural damage in several communities and much damage to property.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Anchorage sustained great destruction or damage to many inadequately earthquake-engineered houses, buildings, and infrastructure (paved streets, sidewalks, water and sewer mains, electrical systems, and other human-made equipment), particularly in the several landslide zones along Knik Arm.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Two hundred miles (320 km) southwest, some areas near Kodiak were permanently raised by 30 feet (9 m).
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Southeast of Anchorage, areas around the head of Turnagain Arm near Girdwood and Portage dropped as much as 8 feet (2.4 m), requiring reconstruction and fill to raise the Seward Highway above the new high tide mark.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] In Prince William Sound, Port Valdez suffered a massive underwater landslide, resulting in the deaths of 32 people between the collapse of the Valdez city harbor and docks, and inside the ship that was docked there at the time.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Nearby, a 27-foot (8.2 m) tsunami destroyed the village of Chenega, killing 23 of the 68 people who lived there; survivors out-ran the wave, climbing to high ground.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Post-quake tsunamis severely affected Whittier, Seward, Kodiak, and other Alaskan communities, as well as people and property in British Columbia, Washington, Oregon, and California.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Tsunamis also caused damage in Hawaii and Japan.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Evidence of motion directly related to the earthquake was also reported from Florida and Texas.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Alaska had never experienced a major disaster in a highly populated area before and had very limited resources for dealing with the effects of such an event.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] In Anchorage, at the urging of geologist Lidia Selkregg, the City of Anchorage and the Alaska State Housing Authority appointed a team of 40 scientists, including geologists, soil scientists, and engineers, to assess the damage done by the earthquake to the city.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] The team, called the Engineering and Geological Evaluation Group, was headed by Ruth A.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Schmidt, a geology professor at the University of Alaska Anchorage.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] The team of scientists came into conflict with local developers and downtown business owners who wanted to immediately rebuild; the scientists wanted to identify future dangers to ensure that the rebuilt infrastructure would be safe.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] The team produced a report on May 8, 1964, just a little more than a month after the earthquake.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] The United States military, which has a large active presence in Alaska, also stepped in to assist within moments of the end of the quake.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Army rapidly re-established communications with the lower 48 states, deployed troops to assist the citizens of Anchorage, and dispatched a convoy to Valdez.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] On the advice of military and civilian leaders, President Lyndon B.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Johnson declared all of Alaska a major disaster area the day after the quake.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Coast Guard deployed ships to isolated coastal communities to assist with immediate needs.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Bad weather and poor visibility hampered air rescue and observation efforts the day after the quake, but on Sunday the 29th the situation improved and rescue helicopters and observation aircraft were deployed.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] A military airlift immediately began shipping relief supplies to Alaska, eventually delivering 2,570,000 pounds (1,170,000 kg) of food and other supplies.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Broadcast journalist, Genie Chance, assisted in recovery and relief efforts, staying on the KENI air waves over Anchorage for more than 24 continuous hours as the voice of calm from her temporary post within the Anchorage Public Safety Building.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] She was effectively designated as the public safety officer by the city's police chief.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Army Corps of Engineers led the effort to rebuild roads, clear debris, and establish new townsites for communities that had been completely destroyed, at a cost of $110 million.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] The West Coast and Alaska Tsunami Warning Center was formed as a direct response to the disaster.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Federal disaster relief funds paid for reconstruction as well as financially supporting the devastated infrastructure of Alaska's government, spending hundreds of millions of dollars that helped keep Alaska financially solvent until the discovery of massive oil deposits at Prudhoe Bay.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Defense Department, the Alaska National Guard founded the Alaska Division of Emergency Services to respond to any future disasters.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] The 1968 discovery of oil at Prudhoe Bay and the 1977 completion of the Trans-Alaska Pipeline System led to an oil boom.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Royalty revenues from oil have funded large state budgets from 1980 onward.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Oil production was not the only economic value of Alaska's land.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] In the second half of the 20th century, Alaska discovered tourism as an important source of revenue.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Tourism became popular after World War II when military personnel stationed in the region returned home praising its natural splendor.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] The Alcan Highway, built during the war, and the Alaska Marine Highway System, completed in 1963, made the state more accessible than before.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Tourism has become increasingly important in Alaska, and today more than 1.4 million people visit the state each year.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] With tourism more vital to the economy, environmentalism rose in importance.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Because of the Act, Alaska now contains two-thirds of all American national parklands.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Today, more than half of Alaskan land is owned by the Federal Government.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] In 1989, the *Exxon Valdez* hit a reef in the Prince William Sound, spilling more than 11 million gallons (42 megalitres) of crude oil over 1,100 miles (1,800 km) of coastline.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Today, the battle between philosophies of development and conservation is seen in the contentious debate over oil drilling in the Arctic National Wildlife Refuge and the proposed Pebble Mine.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Located at the northwest corner of North America very near to Asia, Alaska is the northernmost and westernmost state in the United States, but also has the most easterly longitude in the United States because the Aleutian Islands extend into the Eastern Hemisphere.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Alaska is the only non-contiguous U.S. state on continental North America; about 500 miles (800 km) of Canadian territory consisting of British Columbia (in Canada) separates Alaska from Washington.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] It is technically part of the continental U.S., but is not usually included in the colloquial use of the term; Alaska is not part of the contiguous U.S., often called "the Lower 48".
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] The capital city, Juneau, is situated on the mainland of the North American continent but is not connected by road to the rest of the North American highway system.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] The largest lake in Alaska is Lake Illiamna.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Alaska is bordered by Canada's Yukon and British Columbia to the east (making it the only state to border only a Canadian territory); the Gulf of Alaska and the Pacific Ocean to the south and southwest; the Bering Sea, Bering Strait, and Chukchi Sea to the west; and the Arctic Ocean to the north.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Alaska's territorial waters touch Russia's territorial waters in the Bering Strait, as the Russian Big Diomede Island and Alaskan Little Diomede Island are only 3 miles (4.8 km) apart.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Alaska has a longer coastline than all the other U.S. states combined.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] At 663,268 square miles (1,717,856 km2) in total area, Alaska is by far the largest state in the United States.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Alaska is more than twice the size of the second-largest U.S. state (Texas), and it is larger than the next three largest states (Texas, California, and Montana) combined.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Alaska is the seventh largest subnational division in the world.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] If it was an independent nation, it would be the 18th largest country in the world; almost the same size as Iran.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] With its myriad islands, Alaska has nearly 34,000 miles (55,000 km) of tidal shoreline.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] The Aleutian Islands chain extends west from the southern tip of the Alaska Peninsula.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Many active volcanoes are found in the Aleutians and in coastal regions.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Unimak Island, for example, is home to Mount Shishaldin, which is an occasionally smoldering volcano that rises to 10,000 feet (3,000 m) above the North Pacific.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] The chain of volcanoes extends to Mount Spurr, west of Anchorage on the mainland.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Geologists have identified Alaska as part of Wrangellia, a large region consisting of multiple states and Canadian provinces in the Pacific Northwest, which is actively undergoing continent building.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] One of the world's largest tides occurs in Turnagain Arm, just south of Anchorage, where tidal differences can be more than 35 feet (10.7 m).
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Alaska has more than 409,000 natural lakes at least one hectare or bigger.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Marshlands and wetland permafrost cover 188,320 square miles (487,700 km2) (mostly in northern, western and southwest flatlands).
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Glacier ice covers about 28,957 square miles (75,000 km2) of Alaska.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] The Bering Glacier is the largest glacier in North America, covering 2,008 square miles (5,200 km2) alone.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] The most populous region of Alaska contains Anchorage, the Matanuska-Susitna Valley and the Kenai Peninsula.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Rural, mostly unpopulated areas south of the Alaska Range and west of the Wrangell Mountains also fall within the definition of South Central, as do the Prince William Sound area and the communities of Cordova and Valdez.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Also referred to as the Panhandle or Inside Passage, this is the region of Alaska closest to the contiguous states.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] As such, this was where most of the initial non-indigenous settlement occurred in the years following the Alaska Purchase.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] The region is dominated by the Alexander Archipelago as well as the Tongass National Forest, the largest national forest in the United States.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] It contains the state capital Juneau, the former capital Sitka, and Ketchikan, at one time Alaska's largest city.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] The Alaska Marine Highway provides a vital surface transportation link throughout the area and country, as only three communities (Haines, Hyder and Skagway) enjoy direct connections to the contiguous North American road system.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] The Interior is the largest region of Alaska; much of it is uninhabited wilderness.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Fairbanks is the only large city in the region.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Denali National Park and Preserve is located here.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Denali, federally designated as Mount McKinley, is the highest mountain in North America and is also located here.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] The North Slope is mostly tundra peppered with small villages.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] The area is known for its massive reserves of crude oil and contains both the National Petroleum Reserve–Alaska and the Prudhoe Bay Oil Field.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] The city of Utqiaġvik, formerly known as Barrow, is the northernmost city in the United States and is located here.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] The Northwest Arctic area, anchored by Kotzebue and also containing the Kobuk River valley, is often considered part of this region.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] The respective Inupiat of the North Slope and of the Northwest Arctic seldom consider themselves to be one people.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Southwest Alaska is a sparsely inhabited region stretching some 500 miles (800 km) inland from the Bering Sea.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Most of the population lives along the coast.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Kodiak Island is also located in the Southwest.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] The massive Yukon–Kuskokwim Delta, one of the largest river deltas in the world, is here.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Portions of the Alaska Peninsula are considered part of the Southwest, with the Aleutian Islands often (but not always) being grouped in as well.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] While primarily part of Southwest Alaska when grouped economically, the Aleutian islands are sometimes recognized as an alternate group from the rest of the region due to the geographic separation from the continent.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] More than 300 small volcanic islands make up this chain, which stretches more than 1,200 miles (1,900 km) into the Pacific Ocean.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Some of these islands fall in the Eastern Hemisphere, but the International Date Line was drawn west of 180° to keep the whole state, and thus the entire North American continent, within the same legal day.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Two of the islands, Attu and Kiska, were occupied by Japanese forces during World War II.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] As of 2023 the United States Bureau of Land Management manages 290 million surface and subsurface acres as public lands, including a multitude of national forests, national parks, national wildlife refuges, and federal mineral estate land.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Of these, the Bureau of Land Management manages 87 million acres (35 million hectares), or 23.8% of the state.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] The Arctic National Wildlife Refuge is managed by the United States Fish and Wildlife Service.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] It is the world's largest wildlife refuge, comprising 16 million acres (6.5 million hectares).
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Of the remaining land area, the state of Alaska owns 101 million acres (41 million hectares), its entitlement under the Alaska Statehood Act.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] A portion of that acreage is occasionally ceded to the organized boroughs presented above, under the statutory provisions pertaining to newly formed boroughs.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Smaller portions are set aside for rural subdivisions and other homesteading-related opportunities.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] These are not very popular due to the often remote and roadless locations.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] The University of Alaska, as a land grant university, also owns substantial acreage which it manages independently.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Another 44 million acres (18 million hectares) are owned by 12 regional, and scores of local, Native corporations created under the Alaska Native Claims Settlement Act (ANCSA) of 1971.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Regional Native corporation Doyon, Limited often promotes itself as the largest private landowner in Alaska in advertisements and other communications.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Provisions of ANCSA allowing the corporations' land holdings to be sold on the open market starting in 1991 were repealed before they could take effect.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Effectively, the corporations hold title (including subsurface title in many cases, a privilege denied to individual Alaskans) but cannot sell the land.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Individual Native allotments are sold on the open market.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Various private interests own the remaining land, totaling about one percent of the state.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Alaska is, by a large margin, the state with the smallest percentage of private land ownership when Native corporation holdings are excluded.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] The Alaska Heritage Resources Survey (AHRS) is a restricted inventory of all reported historic and prehistoric sites within the U.S. state of Alaska; it is maintained by the Office of History and Archaeology.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] The survey's inventory of cultural resources includes objects, structures, buildings, sites, districts, and travel ways, with a general provision that they are more than fifty years old.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] As of 31 January 2012, more than 35,000 sites have been reported.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Unlike most of U.S. states, Alaska is not divided into counties.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Similarly to Louisiana's parishes, it is divided into *boroughs*.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Delegates to the Alaska Constitutional Convention wanted to avoid the pitfalls of the traditional county system and adopted their own unique model.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Many of the more densely populated parts of the state are part of Alaska's 16 boroughs, which function somewhat similarly to counties in other states.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Unlike county-equivalents in the other states, the boroughs do not cover the state's entire land area.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] The area not part of any borough is referred to as the Unorganized Borough.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] The Unorganized Borough has no government of its own, but the U.S.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Census Bureau in cooperation with the state divided the Unorganized Borough into 11 census areas solely for the purposes of statistical analysis and presentation.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] A *recording district* is a mechanism for management of the public record in Alaska.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] The state is divided into 34 recording districts which are centrally administered under a state recorder.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] All recording districts use the same acceptance criteria, fee schedule, etc., for accepting documents into the public record.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Whereas many U.S. states use a three-tiered system of decentralization—state/county/township—most of Alaska uses two tiers—state/borough.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Owing to the low population density, most of the land is located in the Unorganized Borough.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] As the name implies, it has no intermediate borough government but is administered directly by the state government.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] In 2000, 57.71% of Alaska's area has this status, with 13.05% of the population.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] In 1975, Anchorage merged the city government with the Greater Anchorage Area Borough to form the Municipality of Anchorage, containing the city proper and the communities of Eagle River, Chugiak, Peters Creek, Girdwood, Bird, and Indian.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Fairbanks has a separate borough (the Fairbanks North Star Borough) and municipality (the City of Fairbanks).
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Alaska's most populous city is Anchorage, home to 291,247 people in 2020.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] The richest location in Alaska by per capita income is Denali ($42,245).
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Yakutat, Sitka, Juneau, and Anchorage are the four largest cities in the U.S. by area.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] In the 2020 United States census, Alaska has 355 incorporated cities and census-designated places (CDPs).
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] The tally of cities includes four unified municipalities, essentially the equivalent of a consolidated city–county.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] The majority of these communities are located in the rural expanse of Alaska known as "The Bush" and are unconnected to that contiguous North American road network.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] The table at the bottom of this section lists the 100 largest cities and census-designated places in Alaska, in population order.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Of Alaska's 2020 U.S. census population figure of 733,391, 16,655 people, or 2.27% of the population, did not live in an incorporated city or census-designated place.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Approximately three-quarters of that figure were people who live in urban and suburban neighborhoods on the outskirts of the city limits of Ketchikan, Kodiak, Palmer and Wasilla.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] CDPs have not been established for these areas by the United States Census Bureau.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Seven CDPs were established for the Ketchikan-area neighborhoods in the 1980 census (Clover Pass, Herring Cove, Ketchikan East, Mountain Point, Alaska Route 7, Pennock Island and Saxman East), but have not been used since.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] The remaining population was scattered throughout Alaska, both within organized boroughs and in the Unorganized Borough, in largely remote areas.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Alaska is the coldest state in the United States.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] The climate in the south and southeastern Alaska is a mid-latitude oceanic climate (Köppen climate classification: *Cfb*), and a subarctic oceanic climate (Köppen *Cfc*) in the northern parts, with cool summers and relatively mild winters.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] On an annual basis, the southeast is both the wettest and warmest part of Alaska with milder temperatures in the winter and high precipitation throughout the year.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Juneau averages over 50 in (130 cm) of precipitation a year, and Ketchikan averages over 150 in (380 cm).
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] This is also the only region in Alaska in which the average daytime high temperature is above freezing during the winter months.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] The climate of Anchorage and south central Alaska is mild by Alaskan standards due to the region's proximity to the seacoast.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] While the area gets less rain than southeast Alaska, it gets more snow, and days tend to be clearer.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] On average, Anchorage receives 16 in (41 cm) of precipitation a year, with around 75 in (190 cm) of snow, although there are areas in the south central which receive far more snow.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] It is a subarctic climate (Köppen: *Dfc*) due to its brief, cool summers.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] The climate of western Alaska is determined in large part by the Bering Sea and the Gulf of Alaska.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] It is a subarctic oceanic climate in the southwest and a continental subarctic climate farther north.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] The temperature is somewhat moderate considering how far north the area is.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] This region has a tremendous amount of variety in precipitation.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] An area stretching from the northern side of the Seward Peninsula to the Kobuk River valley (i.e., the region around Kotzebue Sound) is technically a desert, with portions receiving less than 10 in (25 cm) of precipitation annually.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] On the other extreme, some locations between Dillingham and Bethel average around 100 in (250 cm) of precipitation.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] The climate of the interior of Alaska is subarctic and is a classic example of a continental subarctic climate, except in a few valleys where the climate approaches humid continental (Köppen: *Dfb*).
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Some of the highest and lowest temperatures in Alaska occur around the area near Fairbanks.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Summers are warm, albeit generally short, and may have temperatures reaching into the 90s °F (the low-to-mid 30s °C).
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] In the long and very cold winters, the temperature can fall below −60 °F (−51 °C).
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Precipitation is sparse in the Interior, often less than 10 in (25 cm) a year, but what precipitation falls in the winter tends to stay the entire winter.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] The highest and lowest recorded temperatures in Alaska are both in the Interior.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] The highest is 100 °F (38 °C) in Fort Yukon, which is just 8 mi or 13 km inside the arctic circle, on June 27, 1915, making Alaska tied with Hawaii as the state with the lowest high temperature in the United States.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] The lowest official Alaska temperature is −80 °F (−62 °C) in Prospect Creek on January 23, 1971, one degree above the lowest temperature recorded in continental North America (in Snag, Yukon, Canada).
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] The climate in the extreme north of Alaska, north of the Brooks Range, is Arctic (Köppen: *ET*) with long, very cold winters and short, cool summers.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Even in July, the average low temperature in Utqiaġvik is 34 °F (1 °C).
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Precipitation is light in this part of Alaska, with many places averaging less than 10 in (25 cm) per year, mostly as snow which stays on the ground almost the entire year.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] The United States Census Bureau found in the 2020 United States census that the population of Alaska was 733,391 on April 1, 2020, a 3.3% increase since the 2010 United States census.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] In the 2010 United States Census, Alaska had a population of 710,231, an increase of 13.3%, up from 626,932 at the 2000 U.S. census.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] In 2020, Alaska ranked as the 48th largest state by population, ahead of only Vermont and Wyoming.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Alaska is the least densely populated state, and one of the most sparsely populated areas in the world, at 1.2 inhabitants per square mile (0.46/km2).
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] The next state, Wyoming, has 5.8 inhabitants per square mile (2.2/km2).
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Alaska is by far the largest U.S. state by area, and the tenth wealthiest, per capita income.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] As of 2018 due to its population size, it is one of 14 U.S. states that still have only one telephone area code.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] In HUD's 2022 Annual Homeless Assessment Report, there were an estimated 2,320 homeless people in Alaska.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] The 2019 American Community Survey estimated 60.2% of the population was white, 3.7% black or African American, 15.6% American Indian or Alaska Native, 6.5% Asian, 1.4% Native Hawaiian and other Pacific Islander, 7.5% two or more races, and 7.3% Hispanic or Latin American.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] At the survey estimates, 7.8% of the total population was foreign-born from 2015 to 2019.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] In 2015, 61.3% were white, 3.4% black or African American, 13.3% American Indian or Alaska Native, 6.2% Asian, 0.9% Native Hawaiian and other Pacific Islander, 0.3% some other race, and 7.7% multiracial.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Hispanics and Latin Americans were 7% of the state population in 2015.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] From 2015 to 2019, the largest Hispanic and Latin American groups were Mexican Americans, Puerto Ricans, and Cuban Americans.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] The largest Asian groups living in the state were Filipinos, Korean Americans, and Japanese and Chinese Americans.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] In 2010, Alaska was 64.1% white, 14.8% American Indian and Alaska Native, 5.4% Asian, 3.3% black or African American, 1.0% Native Hawaiian and other Pacific Islander, 1.6% from some other race, and 7.3% from two or more races in 2010.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Hispanics or Latin Americans made up 5.5% of the population in 2010.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] As of 2011, 50.7% of Alaska's population younger than one year of age belonged to minority groups (i.e., did not have two parents of white ancestry).
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] In 1960, the United States Census Bureau reported Alaska's population as 77.2% white, 3% black, and 18.8% American Indian and Alaska Native.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] In 2018, the top countries of origin for Alaska's immigrants were the Philippines, Mexico, Canada, Thailand and South Korea.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] In the 2011 American Community Survey, 83.4% of people over the age of five spoke only English at home.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] About 3.5% spoke Spanish at home, 2.2% spoke another Indo-European language, about 4.3% spoke an Asian language (including Tagalog), and about 5.3% spoke other languages at home.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] In 2019, the American Community Survey determined 83.7% spoke only English, and 16.3% spoke another language other than English.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] The most spoken European language after English was Spanish, spoken by approximately 4.0% of the state population.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Collectively, Asian and Pacific Islander languages were spoken by 5.6% of Alaskans.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Since 2010, 5.2% of Alaskans speak one of the state's 20 Indigenous languages, known locally as "Native languages".
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Alaska is also known for a distinctive dialect of Russian, named Alaskan Russian.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] The Alaska Native Language Center at the University of Alaska Fairbanks claims that at least twenty Alaska Native languages exist and there are also some languages with different dialects.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Most of Alaska's Native languages belong to either the Eskimo–Aleut or Na-Dene language families.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Some languages are thought to be isolates (e.g., Haida) or have not yet been classified (e.g., Tsimshianic).
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] In 2014, nearly all of Alaska's Native languages were classified as either threatened, shifting, moribund, nearly extinct, or dormant languages.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] In October 2014, the governor of Alaska signed a bill declaring the state's 20 Indigenous languages to have official status.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] This bill gave them symbolic recognition as official languages, though they have not been adopted for official use within the government.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] In May 2024, a bill replaced Tanana with Middle Tanana and Lower Tanana, added Cupʼig and Wetał.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Multiple surveys have ranked Alaska among the most irreligious states.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] ChangePoint in south Anchorage (left) and Anchorage Baptist Temple in east Anchorage are Alaska's largest churches in terms of attendance and membership.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] In 2010, per the Association of Religion Data Archives (ARDA), about 34% of Alaska residents were members of religious congregations.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Of the religious population, roughly 4% were Mormon, 0.5% Jewish, 0.5% Muslim, 1% Buddhist, 0.2% Baháʼí, and 0.5% Hindu.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] In 2010, the largest religious denominations in Alaska were the Catholic Church with 50,866 adherents; non-denominational Evangelicals with 38,070 adherents; The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints with 32,170 adherents; and the Southern Baptist Convention with 19,891 adherents.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Alaska has been identified, along with Washington and Oregon in the Pacific Northwest, as being the least religious states in the United States, in terms of church membership.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] The Pew Research Center in 2014 determined 62% of the adult population practiced Christianity.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Of the Christian denominations, Catholicism was the largest Christian group.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] When Protestant denominations were combined, Protestantism was the largest Christian tradition, with Evangelicalism being the largest movement within the Protestant group.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] The unaffiliated population made up the largest non-Christian religious affiliation at 37%.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Atheists made up 5% of the population and the largest non-Christian religion was Buddhism.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] In 2020, the Public Religion Research Institute (PRRI) determined 57% of adults were Christian.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] By 2022, Christianity increased to 77% of the population according to the PRRI.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Through the Association of Religion Data Archives in 2020, its Christian population was dominated by non/inter-denominational Protestantism as the single largest Christian cohort, with 73,930 adherents.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Roman Catholics were second with 40,280 members; throughout its Christian population, non-denominational Christians had an adherence rate of 100.81 per 1,000 residents, and Catholics 54.92 per 1,000 residents.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Per 2014's Pew study, religion was seen as very important to 41% of the population, although 29% considered it somewhat important.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] In 2014, Pew determined roughly 55% believed in God with absolute certainty, and 24% believed fairly certainly.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Reflecting the separate 2020 ARDA study, the 2014 Pew study showed 30% attended religious services once a week, 34% once or twice a month, and 36% seldom/never.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] In 1795, the first Russian Orthodox Church was established in Kodiak.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Intermarriage with Alaska Natives helped the Russian immigrants integrate into society.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] As a result, an increasing number of Russian Orthodox churches gradually became established within Alaska.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Alaska also has the largest Quaker population (by percentage) of any state.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] In 2009, there were 6,000 Jews in Alaska, for whom observance of halakha may pose special problems.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Alaskan Hindus often share venues and celebrations with members of other Asian religious communities, including Sikhs and Jains.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] In 2010, Alaskan Hindus established the Sri Ganesha Temple of Alaska, making it the first Hindu Temple in Alaska and the northernmost Hindu Temple in the world.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] There are an estimated 2,000–3,000 Hindus in Alaska.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] The vast majority of Hindus live in Anchorage or Fairbanks.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Estimates for the number of Muslims in Alaska range from 2,000 to 5,000.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] In 2020, ARDA estimated there were 400 Muslims in the state.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] The Islamic Community Center of Anchorage began efforts in the late 1990s to construct a mosque in Anchorage.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] They broke ground on a building in south Anchorage in 2010 and were nearing completion in late 2014.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] When completed, the mosque was the first in the state and one of the northernmost mosques in the world.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] There is also a Baháʼí center, and there were 690 adherents in 2020.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p01] Additionally, there were 469 adherents of Hinduism and Yoga altogether in 2020, and a small number of Buddhists were present.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] In October 2022, Alaska had a total employment of 316,900.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] The number of employer establishments was 21,077.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] As of August 2025, the unemployment rate was 4.7%.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] The state's historically lowest unemployment rate was recorded in August 2022 at 3.8%, and its highest in May 2020 at 11.7%.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Bureau of Economic Analysis, Alaska's gross state product was $75.011 billion in 2025.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Its per capita personal income was $80,175 in 2025.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] According to a 2013 study by Phoenix Marketing International, Alaska had the fifth-largest number of millionaires per capita in the United States, with a ratio of 6.75 percent.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] The oil and gas industry dominates the Alaskan economy, with more than 80% of the state's revenues derived from petroleum extraction.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Alaska's main export product, excluding oil and natural gas, is seafood, primarily salmon, cod, pollock and crab.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Agriculture represents a minuscule fraction of the Alaskan economy.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Agricultural production is primarily for consumption within the state and includes nursery stock, dairy products, vegetables, and livestock.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Manufacturing is limited, with most foodstuffs and general goods imported from elsewhere.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Employment is primarily in government and industries such as natural resource extraction, shipping, and transportation.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Military bases are a significant component of the economy in Anchorage and the Fairbanks North Star and Kodiak Island boroughs.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] In 2025, 99.1% of Alaska businesses are small businesses and employ 54.2% of the state's workforce.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Federal subsidies are also an important part of the economy, allowing the state to keep taxes low.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Its industrial outputs are crude petroleum, natural gas, coal, gold, precious metals, zinc and other mining, seafood processing, timber and wood products.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] There is also a growing service and tourism sector.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Tourists have contributed to the economy by supporting local lodging.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Alaska has vast energy resources, although its oil reserves have been largely depleted.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Major oil and gas reserves were found in the Alaska North Slope (ANS) and Cook Inlet basins, but according to the Energy Information Administration, by February 2014 Alaska had fallen to fourth place in the nation in crude oil production after Texas, North Dakota, and California.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Prudhoe Bay on Alaska's North Slope is still the second highest-yielding oil field in the United States, typically producing about 400,000 barrels per day (64,000 m3/d), although by early 2014 North Dakota's Bakken Formation was producing over 900,000 barrels per day (140,000 m3/d).
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] The Trans-Alaska Pipeline can transport and pump up to 2.1 million barrels (330,000 m3) of crude oil per day, more than any other crude oil pipeline in the United States.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Substantial coal deposits are found in Alaska's bituminous, sub-bituminous, and lignite coal basins.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] The United States Geological Survey estimates that there are 85.4 trillion cubic feet (2,420 km3) of undiscovered, technically recoverable gas from natural gas hydrates on the Alaskan North Slope.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Alaska also offers some of the highest hydroelectric power potential in the country from its numerous rivers.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Large swaths of the Alaskan coastline offer wind and geothermal energy potential as well.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Alaska's economy depends heavily on increasingly expensive diesel fuel for heating, transportation, electric power and light.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Although wind and hydroelectric power are abundant and underdeveloped, proposals for statewide energy systems were judged uneconomical (at the time of the report, 2001) due to low (less than 50¢/gal) fuel prices, long distances and low population.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] The Alaska Permanent Fund is a constitutionally authorized appropriation of oil revenues, established by voters in 1976 to manage a surplus in state petroleum revenues from oil, largely in anticipation of the then recently constructed Trans-Alaska Pipeline System.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] The fund was originally proposed by Governor Keith Miller on the eve of the 1969 Prudhoe Bay lease sale, out of fear that the legislature would spend the entire proceeds of the sale (which amounted to $900 million) at once.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] It was later championed by Governor Jay Hammond and Kenai state representative Hugh Malone.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] It has served as an attractive political prospect ever since, diverting revenues which would normally be deposited into the general fund.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] The Alaska Constitution was written so as to discourage dedicating state funds for a particular purpose.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] The Permanent Fund has become the rare exception to this, mostly due to the political climate of distrust existing during the time of its creation.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] From its initial principal of $734,000, the fund has grown to $50 billion as a result of oil royalties and capital investment programs.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Most if not all the principal is invested conservatively outside Alaska.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] This has led to frequent calls by Alaskan politicians for the Fund to make investments within Alaska, though such a stance has never gained momentum.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Every year, the state legislature takes out 8% from the earnings, puts 3% back into the principal for inflation proofing, and the remaining 5% is distributed to all qualifying Alaskans.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] The Permanent Fund is often considered to be one of the leading examples of a basic income policy in the world.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] The cost of goods in Alaska has long been higher than in the contiguous 48 states.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Federal government employees, particularly United States Postal Service (USPS) workers and active-duty military members, receive a Cost of Living Allowance usually set at 25% of base pay because, while the cost of living has gone down, it is still one of the highest in the country.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Rural Alaska suffers from severely high prices for food and consumer goods compared to the rest of the country, due to the relatively limited transportation infrastructure.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Due to the northern climate and short growing season, relatively little farming occurs in Alaska.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Most farms are in either the Matanuska Valley, about 40 miles (64 km) northeast of Anchorage, or on the Kenai Peninsula, about 60 miles (97 km) southwest of Anchorage.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] The short 100-day growing season limits the crops that can be grown, but the long sunny summer days make for productive growing seasons.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] The primary crops are potatoes, carrots, lettuce, and cabbage.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] The Tanana Valley is another notable agricultural locus, especially the Delta Junction area, about 100 miles (160 km) southeast of Fairbanks, with a sizable concentration of farms growing agronomic crops; these farms mostly lie north and east of Fort Greely.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] This area was largely set aside and developed under a state program spearheaded by Hammond during his second term as governor.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Delta-area crops consist predominantly of barley and hay.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] West of Fairbanks lies another concentration of small farms catering to restaurants, the hotel and tourist industry, and community-supported agriculture.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Alaskan agriculture has experienced a surge in growth of market gardeners, small farms and farmers' markets in recent years, with the highest percentage increase (46%) in the nation in growth in farmers' markets in 2011, compared to 17% nationwide.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] The peony industry has also taken off, as the growing season allows farmers to harvest during a gap in supply elsewhere in the world, thereby filling a niche in the flower market.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Alaska, with no counties, lacks county fairs.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Instead, a small assortment of state and local fairs (with the Alaska State Fair in Palmer the largest), are held mostly in the late summer.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] The fairs are mostly located in communities with historic or current agricultural activity, and feature local farmers exhibiting produce in addition to more high-profile commercial activities such as carnival rides, concerts and food.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] "Alaska Grown" is used as an agricultural slogan.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Alaska has an abundance of seafood, with the primary fisheries in the Bering Sea and the North Pacific.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Seafood is one of the few food items that is often cheaper within the state than outside it.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Many Alaskans take advantage of salmon seasons to harvest portions of their household diet while fishing for subsistence, as well as sport.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] This includes fish taken by hook, net or wheel.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Hunting for subsistence, primarily caribou, moose, and Dall sheep is still common in the state, particularly in remote Bush communities.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] An example of a traditional native food is Akutaq, the Eskimo ice cream, which can consist of reindeer fat, seal oil, dried fish meat and local berries.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Alaska's reindeer herding is concentrated on Seward Peninsula, where wild caribou can be prevented from mingling and migrating with the domesticated reindeer.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Most food in Alaska is transported into the state from "Outside" (the other 49 U.S. states), and shipping costs make food in the cities relatively expensive.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] In rural areas, subsistence hunting and gathering is an essential activity because imported food is prohibitively expensive.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Although most small towns and villages in Alaska lie along the coastline, the cost of importing food to remote villages can be high because of the terrain and difficult road conditions, which change dramatically due to varying climate and precipitation changes.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Transport costs can reach 50¢ per pound ($1.10/kg) or higher in some remote areas during times of inclement weather or rough terrain conditions, if these locations can be reached at all.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] The cost of delivering a gallon (3.8 L) of milk is about $3.50 in many villages where per capita income can be $20,000 or less.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Fuel cost per gallon is routinely twenty to thirty cents higher than the contiguous United States average, with only Hawaii having higher prices.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Some of Alaska's popular annual events are the Iditarod Trail Sled Dog Race from Anchorage to Nome, World Ice Art Championships in Fairbanks, the Blueberry Festival and Alaska Hummingbird Festival in Ketchikan, the Sitka Whale Fest, and the Stikine River Garnet Fest in Wrangell.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] The Stikine River attracts the largest springtime concentration of American bald eagles in the world.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] The Alaska Native Heritage Center celebrates the rich heritage of Alaska's 11 cultural groups.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Their purpose is to encourage cross-cultural exchanges among all people and enhance self-esteem among Native people.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] The Alaska Native Arts Foundation promotes and markets Native art from all regions and cultures in the State, using the internet.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Influences on music in Alaska include the traditional music of Alaska Natives as well as folk music brought by later immigrants from Russia and Europe.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Prominent musicians from Alaska include singer Jewel, traditional Aleut flautist Mary Youngblood, folk singer-songwriter Libby Roderick, Christian music singer-songwriter Lincoln Brewster, metal/post hardcore band 36 Crazyfists and the groups Pamyua and Portugal.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] There are many established music festivals in Alaska, including the Alaska Folk Festival, the Fairbanks Summer Arts Festival, the Anchorage Folk Festival, the Athabascan Old-Time Fiddling Festival, the Sitka Jazz Festival, the Sitka Summer Music Festival, and the Anchorage Chamber Music Festival.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] The most prominent orchestra in Alaska is the Anchorage Symphony Orchestra, though the Fairbanks Symphony Orchestra and Juneau Symphony are also notable.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] The Anchorage Opera is currently the state's only professional opera company, though there are several volunteer and semi-professional organizations in the state as well.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] The official state song of Alaska is "Alaska's Flag", which was adopted in 1955; it celebrates the flag of Alaska.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] The 1983 Disney movie *Never Cry Wolf* was at least partially shot in Alaska.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] The 1991 film *White Fang*, based on Jack London's 1906 novel and starring Ethan Hawke, was filmed in and around Haines.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Steven Seagal's 1994 *On Deadly Ground*, starring Michael Caine, was filmed in part at the Worthington Glacier near Valdez.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Many reality television shows are filmed in Alaska.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] In 2011, the *Anchorage Daily News* found ten set in the state.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] The following is a list of sporting venues, events, and teams based in Alaska.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] The Alaska State Troopers are Alaska's statewide police force.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] They have a long and storied history, but were not an official organization until 1941.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Before the force was officially organized, law enforcement in Alaska was handled by various federal agencies.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Larger towns usually have their own local police and some villages rely on "Public Safety Officers" who have police training but do not carry firearms.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] In much of the state, the troopers serve as the only police force available.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] In addition to enforcing traffic and criminal law, wildlife Troopers enforce hunting and fishing regulations.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Due to the varied terrain and wide scope of the Troopers' duties, they employ a wide variety of land, air, and water patrol vehicles.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Many rural communities in Alaska are considered "dry", having outlawed the importation of alcoholic beverages.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Suicide rates for rural residents are higher than urban rates.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Domestic abuse and other violent crimes are at high levels in Alaska.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] This is in part linked to alcohol abuse.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Alaska has the highest rate of sexual assault in the nation, especially in rural areas.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] The average age of sexually assaulted victims is 16 years old.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] In four out of five cases, the suspects were relatives, friends, or acquaintances.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] As of 2022, CVS Health and Premera account for 47% and 46% of private health insurance, respectively.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Premera and Moda Health offer insurance on the federally-run Affordable Care Exchange.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Providence Alaska Medical Center in Anchorage is the largest hospital in the state as of 2021; Anchorage also hosts Alaska Regional Hospital and Alaska Native Medical Center.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Alaska's other major cities such as Fairbanks and Juneau also have local hospitals.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] In Southeast Alaska, Southeast Alaska Regional Health Consortium, runs healthcare facilities across 27 communities as of 2022, including hospitals in Sitka and Wrangell; although it originally served Native Americans only, it has expanded access and combined with other local facilities over time.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] The Alaska Department of Education and Early Development administers many school districts in Alaska.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] In addition, the state operates a boarding school, Mt.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Edgecumbe High School in Sitka, and provides partial funding for other boarding schools, including Nenana Student Living Center in Nenana and The Galena Interior Learning Academy in Galena.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] There are more than a dozen colleges and universities in Alaska.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Accredited universities in Alaska include the University of Alaska Anchorage, University of Alaska Fairbanks, University of Alaska Southeast, and Alaska Pacific University.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Alaska is the only state that has no collegiate athletic programs that are members of NCAA Division I, although both Alaska-Fairbanks and Alaska-Anchorage maintain single sport membership in Division I for men's ice hockey.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] The Alaska Department of Labor and Workforce Development operates AVTEC, Alaska's Institute of Technology.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Campuses in Seward and Anchorage offer one-week to 11-month training programs in areas as diverse as Information Technology, Welding, Nursing, and Mechanics.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Alaska has had a problem with a "brain drain".
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Many of its young people, including most of the highest academic achievers, leave the state after high school graduation and do not return.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] As of 2013 Alaska did not have a law school or medical school.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] The University of Alaska has attempted to combat this by offering partial four-year scholarships to the top 10% of Alaska high school graduates, via the Alaska Scholars Program.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Beginning in 1998, schools in rural Alaska must have at least ten students to retain funding from the state, and campuses not meeting the number close.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] This was due to the loss in oil revenues that previously propped up smaller rural schools.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] In 2015, there was a proposal to raise that minimum to 25, but legislators in the state largely did not agree.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Alaska has few road connections compared to the rest of the U.S.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] The state's road system, covering a relatively small area of the state, linking the central population centers and the Alaska Highway, the principal route out of the state through Canada.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] The state capital, Juneau, is not accessible by road, with access only by ferry or flight; this has spurred debate over decades about moving the capital to a city on the road system, or building a road connection from Haines.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] The western part of Alaska has no road system connecting the communities with the rest of Alaska.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] The Interstate Highways in Alaska consists of a total of 1,082 miles (1,741 km).
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] These are mostly not built to Interstate Highway standards and their status as such is largely notional.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] A unique feature of the Alaska Highway system is the Anton Anderson Memorial Tunnel, an active Alaska Railroad tunnel that provides a paved roadway link with the isolated community of Whittier on Prince William Sound to the Seward Highway about 50 miles (80 km) southeast of Anchorage at Portage.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] At 2.5 miles (4.0 km), the tunnel was the longest road tunnel in North America until 2007.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] The tunnel is the longest combination road and rail tunnel in North America.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Southwest Alaska is largely coastal, sparsely populated, and unconnected to the road system.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Access to most communities in Southwest Alaska is primarily by air taxi, although larger towns like Kodiak, Bethel, King Salmon, Dillingham, and Dutch Harbor are accessible by scheduled air service.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Some coastal communities can be reached via the Alaska Marine Highway ferry.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Built around 1915, the Alaska Railroad (ARR) played a key role in the development of Alaska through the 20th century.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] It links shipping lanes on the North Pacific with Interior Alaska with tracks that run from Seward by way of South Central Alaska, passing through Anchorage, Eklutna, Wasilla, Talkeetna, Denali, and Fairbanks, with spurs to Whittier, Palmer and North Pole.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] The cities, towns, villages, and region served by ARR tracks are known statewide as "The Railbelt".
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] In recent years, the ever-improving paved highway system began to eclipse the railroad's importance in Alaska's economy.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] The railroad played a vital role in Alaska's development, moving freight into Alaska while transporting natural resources southward, such as coal from the Usibelli coal mine near Healy to Seward and gravel from the Matanuska Valley to Anchorage.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] It is well known for its summertime tour passenger service.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] The Alaska Railroad was one of the last railroads in North America to use cabooses in regular service and still uses them on some gravel trains.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] It continues to offer one of the last flag stop routes in the country.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] A stretch of about 60 miles (100 km) of track along an area north of Talkeetna remains inaccessible by road; the railroad provides the only transportation to rural homes and cabins in the area.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Until construction of the Parks Highway in the 1970s, the railroad provided the only land access to most of the region along its entire route.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] In northern Southeast Alaska, the White Pass and Yukon Route also partly runs through the state from Skagway northwards into Canada (British Columbia and Yukon Territory), crossing the border at White Pass Summit.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] This line is now mainly used by tourists, often arriving by cruise liner at Skagway.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] It was featured in the 1983 BBC television series *Great Little Railways*.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] These two railroads are connected neither to each other nor any other railroad.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] The nearest link to the North American railway network is the northwest terminus of the Canadian National Railway at Prince Rupert, British Columbia, several hundred miles to the southeast.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Congress authorized $6 million to study the feasibility of a rail link between Alaska, Canada, and the lower 48.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] As of 2021 the Alaska-Alberta Railway Development Corporation is in receivership.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Some private companies provides car float service between Whittier and Seattle.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Many cities, towns, and villages in Alaska don't have road or highway access.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] The only modes of access involve travel by air, river, or the sea.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Alaska's well-developed state-owned ferry system, known as the Alaska Marine Highway, serves the cities of southeast, the Gulf Coast and the Alaska Peninsula.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] The ferries transport vehicles and passengers.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] The system also operates a ferry service from Bellingham, Washington and Prince Rupert, British Columbia, in Canada through the Inside Passage to Skagway.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] The Inter-Island Ferry Authority also serves as an important marine link for many communities in the Prince of Wales Island region of Southeast and works in concert with the Alaska Marine Highway.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] In recent years, cruise lines have created a summertime tourism market, mainly connecting the Pacific Northwest to Southeast Alaska and, to a lesser degree, towns along Alaska's gulf coast.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] The population of Ketchikan for example fluctuates dramatically on many days—up to four large cruise ships can dock there at the same time.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Cities not served by road, sea, or river can be reached only by air, foot, dogsled, or snowmachine, accounting for Alaska's extremely well developed bush air services—an Alaskan novelty.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Anchorage, and to a lesser extent Fairbanks, is served by many major airlines.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Because of limited highway access, air travel remains the most efficient form of transportation in and out of the state.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Anchorage recently completed extensive remodeling and construction at Ted Stevens Anchorage International Airport to help accommodate the upsurge in tourism.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] In 2012–2013, Alaska received almost two million visitors.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Making regular flights to most villages and towns within the state commercially viable is difficult, so they are heavily subsidized by the federal government through the Essential Air Service program.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] The bulk of remaining commercial flight offerings come from small regional commuter airlines such as Ravn Alaska, PenAir, and Frontier Flying Service.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] The smallest towns and villages must rely on scheduled or chartered bush flying services using general aviation aircraft such as the Cessna Caravan, the most popular aircraft in use in the state.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Much of this service can be attributed to the Alaska bypass mail program which subsidizes bulk mail delivery to Alaskan rural communities.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] The program requires 70% of that subsidy to go to carriers who offer passenger service to the communities.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Many communities have small air taxi services.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] These operations originated from the demand for customized transport to remote areas.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Perhaps the most quintessentially Alaskan plane is the bush seaplane.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] The world's busiest seaplane base is Lake Hood, located next to Ted Stevens Anchorage International Airport, where flights bound for remote villages without an airstrip carry passengers, cargo, and many items from stores and warehouse clubs.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] In 2006, Alaska had the highest number of pilots per capita of any U.S. state.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] In Alaska there are 8,795 active pilot certificates as of 2020.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Another Alaskan transportation method is the dogsled.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] In modern times, that is, any time after the mid- to late‑1920s, dog mushing is more of a sport than a true means of transportation.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Races are held around the state, but the best known is the Iditarod Trail Sled Dog Race, a 1,150-mile (1,850 km) trail from Anchorage to Nome, although the distance varies from year to year, the official distance is set at 1,049 miles or 1,688 km.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] The race commemorates the famous 1925 serum run to Nome in which mushers and dogs like Togo and Balto took much-needed medicine to the diphtheria-stricken community of Nome when all other means of transportation had failed.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Mushers from all over the world come to Anchorage each March to compete for cash, prizes, and prestige.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] The "Serum Run" is another sled dog race that more accurately follows the route of the famous 1925 relay, leaving from the community of Nenana, southwest of Fairbanks, to Nome.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] In areas not served by road or rail, primary transportation in summer is by fourwheeler and in winter by snowmachine.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Alaska's internet and other data transport systems are provided largely through the two major telecommunications companies: GCI and Alaska Communications.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] GCI owns and operates what it calls the Alaska United Fiber Optic system.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] As of late 2011, Alaska Communications had two fiber optic paths to the lower 48 and two more across Alaska.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] In January 2011, it was reported that a $1 billion project to connect Asia and rural Alaska was being planned, aided in part by $350 million in stimulus from the federal government.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] The state of Alaska employs approximately 16,000 people statewide.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] The Alaska State Legislature consists of a 40-member House of Representatives and a 20-member Senate.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Senators serve four-year terms and House members two.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] The governor of Alaska serves four-year terms.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] The lieutenant governor runs separately from the governor in the primaries, but during the general election, the nominee for governor and nominee for lieutenant governor run together on the same ticket.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Alaska's court system has four levels: the Alaska Supreme Court, the Alaska Court of Appeals, the Superior Court and the district courts.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] The superior and district courts are trial courts.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Superior courts are courts of general jurisdiction, while district courts hear only certain types of cases, including misdemeanor criminal cases and civil cases valued up to $100,000.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] The Supreme Court and the Court of Appeals are appellate courts.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] The Court of Appeals is required to hear appeals from certain lower-court decisions, including those regarding criminal prosecutions, juvenile delinquency, and habeas corpus.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] The Supreme Court hears civil appeals and may in its discretion hear criminal appeals.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Although in its early years of statehood Alaska was a Democratic state, since the early 1970s it has been characterized as Republican-leaning.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Local political communities have often worked on issues related to land use development, fishing, tourism, and individual rights.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Alaska Natives, while organized in and around their communities, have been active within the Native corporations.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] These have been given ownership over large tracts of land, which require stewardship.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Alaska was formerly the only state in which possession of one ounce or less of marijuana in one's home was completely legal under state law, though the federal law remains in force.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] The state has an independence movement favoring a vote on secession from the United States, with the Alaskan Independence Party.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Six Republicans and four Democrats have served as governor of Alaska.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Republican governor Wally Hickel was elected to the office for a second term in 1990 after leaving the Republican party and briefly joining the Alaskan Independence Party ticket just long enough to be reelected.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] He rejoined the Republican party in 1994.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Alaska's voter initiative making marijuana legal took effect in February 2015, placing Alaska alongside Colorado and Washington, as well as Washington D.C., as the first three U.S. states where recreational marijuana is legal.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] The law means people over 21 can consume small amounts of cannabis.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] The first legal marijuana store opened in Valdez in October 2016.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] To finance state government operations, Alaska depends primarily on petroleum revenues and federal subsidies.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] This allows it to have the lowest individual tax burden in the United States.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] It is one of five states with no sales tax, one of seven states with no individual income tax, and—along with New Hampshire—one of two that has neither.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] The Department of Revenue Tax Division reports regularly on the state's revenue sources.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] The department issues an annual summary of its operations, including new state laws that directly affect the tax division.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] In 2014, the Tax Foundation ranked Alaska as having the fourth most "business friendly" tax policy, behind only Wyoming, South Dakota, and Nevada.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] 89 municipalities collect a local sales tax, from 1.0 to 7.5%, typically 3–5%.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Other local taxes levied include raw fish taxes, hotel, motel, and bed-and-breakfast 'bed' taxes, severance taxes, liquor and tobacco taxes, gaming (pull tabs) taxes, tire taxes and fuel transfer taxes.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] A part of the revenue collected from certain state taxes and license fees, such as petroleum, aviation motor fuel, telephone cooperative, is shared with municipalities in Alaska.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] The fall in oil prices after the fracking boom in the early 2010s has decimated Alaska's state treasury, which has historically received about 85 percent of its revenue from taxes and fees imposed on oil and gas companies.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] The state government has had to drastically reduce its budget, and has brought its budget shortfall from over $2 billion in 2016 to under $500 million by 2018.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] In 2020, Alaska's state government budget was $4.8 billion, while projected government revenues were only $4.5 billion.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Alaska regularly supports Republicans in presidential elections and has done so since statehood.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Republicans have won the state's electoral college votes in all but one election that it has participated in (1964).
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] No state has voted for a Democratic presidential candidate fewer times.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Alaska was carried by Democratic nominee Lyndon B.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Johnson during his landslide election in 1964, while the 1960 and 1968 elections were close.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Since 1972, Republicans have carried the state by large margins.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] In 2008, Republican John McCain defeated Democrat Barack Obama in Alaska, 59.49% to 37.83%.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] McCain's running mate was Sarah Palin, the state's governor and the first Alaskan on a major party ticket.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Obama lost Alaska again in 2012, but he captured 40% of the state's vote in that election, making him the first Democrat to do so since 1968.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] In 2020, Joe Biden received 42.77% of the vote for president, marking the high point for a Democratic presidential candidate since Johnson's 1964 victory.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] The Alaska Bush, central Juneau, midtown and downtown Anchorage, and the areas surrounding the University of Alaska Fairbanks campus and Ester have been strongholds of the Democratic Party.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] The Matanuska-Susitna Borough, the Kenai Peninsula, the majority of Fairbanks (including North Pole and the military base), and South Anchorage typically have the strongest Republican showing.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Alaska has a history of primary defeats for incumbent U.S.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Senators, including Ernest Gruening, Mike Gravel, and Lisa Murkowski.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] However, Murkowski won re-election with a write-in campaign.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Despite this, Alaska has also seen long-serving members of Congress, such as Ted Stevens, who served as a U.S.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Senator for 40 years, and Don Young, who held Alaska's sole U.S.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] House seat for 49 years, from 1973 to 2022.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] In the 2020 election cycle, Alaskan voters approved Ballot Measure 2.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] The measure passed by a margin of 1.1%, or about 4,000 votes.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] The measure requires campaigns to disclose the original source and any intermediaries for campaign contributions over $2,000.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] The measure also establishes non-partisan primaries, sometimes called jungle primaries, for statewide elections (like in Washington state and California) and ranked-choice voting, like in Maine.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] Measure 2 makes Alaska the third state with nonpartisan primaries for all statewide races, the second state with ranked choice voting, and the only state with both.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] The 2022 special election to fill Alaska's only U.S.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] House seat, left vacant by the death of Don Young, was won by Mary Peltola.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] She became the first Democrat to win the House seat since 1972 and the first Alaskan Native elected to the United States Congress in history.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-p02] After winning a full term in the 2022 general election, Peltola lost reelection in 2024 to Republican Nick Begich III.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-purchase] The **Alaska Purchase** was the purchase of Alaska from the Russian Empire by the United States for a sum of $7.2 million in 1867 (equivalent to $132 million in 2024).
[src:alaska-day/alaska-purchase] On May 15 of that year, the United States Senate ratified a bilateral treaty that had been signed on March 30, and American sovereignty became legally effective across the territory on October 18.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-purchase] During the first half of the 19th century, Russia had established a colonial presence in parts of North America, but few Russians ever settled in Alaska.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-purchase] Alexander II of Russia, having faced a catastrophic defeat in the Crimean War, began exploring the possibility of selling the state's Alaskan possessions, which, in any future war, would be difficult to defend from the United Kingdom.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-purchase] Seward, the U.S. secretary of state at the time, entered into negotiations with Russian diplomat Eduard de Stoeckl towards the United States' acquisition of Alaska after the American Civil War.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-purchase] Seward and Steckel agreed to a treaty for the sale on March 30, 1867.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-purchase] Reactions to the Alaska Purchase among Americans were mostly positive, as many believed that Alaska would serve as a base to expand American trade in Asia.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-purchase] Some opponents labeled the purchase as "**Seward's Folly**" or "**Seward's Icebox**" as they contended that the United States had acquired useless land.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-purchase] Nearly all Russian settlers left Alaska in the aftermath of the purchase; Alaska would remain sparsely populated until the Klondike Gold Rush began in 1896.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-purchase] Originally organized as the Department of Alaska, the area was renamed the District of Alaska in 1884 and the Territory of Alaska in 1912, ultimately becoming the modern-day state of Alaska in 1959.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-purchase] Russian America was settled by *promyshlenniki*, merchants and fur trappers who expanded through Siberia.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-purchase] They arrived in Alaska in 1732, and in 1799 the Russian-American Company (RAC) received a charter to hunt for fur.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-purchase] No colony was established, but the Russian Orthodox Church sent missionaries to the natives and built churches.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-purchase] About 700 Russians enforced sovereignty in a territory over twice as large as Texas.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-purchase] In 1821, Tsar Alexander I issued an edict declaring Russia's sovereignty over the North American Pacific coast north of the 51st parallel north.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-purchase] The edict also forbade foreign ships to approach within 100 Italian miles (115 miles or 185 km) of the Russian claim.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-purchase] US secretary of state John Quincy Adams strongly protested the edict, which potentially threatened both the commerce and expansionary ambitions of the United States.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-purchase] Seeking favorable relations with the U.S., Alexander agreed to the Russo-American Treaty of 1824.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-purchase] In the treaty, Russia limited its claims to lands north of parallel 54°40′ north and also agreed to open Russian ports to U.S. ships.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-purchase] By the 1850s, a population of once 300,000 sea otters, who were skinned for their valuable fur, was almost extinct, and Russia needed money after being defeated by France and Britain in the Crimean War.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-purchase] The California gold rush showed that if gold were discovered in Alaska, Americans and Canadians would overwhelm the Russian presence in what one scholar later described as "Siberia's Siberia".
[src:alaska-day/alaska-purchase] However, the principal reason for the sale was that the hard-to-defend colony would be easily conquered by British forces based in neighboring Canada in any future conflict, and Russia did not wish to see its archrival being next door just across the Bering Sea.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-purchase] Therefore, Emperor Alexander II decided to sell the territory.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-purchase] The Russian government discussed the proposal in 1857 and 1858 and offered to sell the territory to the United States, hoping that its presence in the region would offset the plans of Britain.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-purchase] However, no deal was reached, as the risk of an American Civil War was a more pressing concern in Washington.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-purchase] Grand Duke Konstantin, a younger brother of the Tsar, began to press for the handover of Russian America to the United States in 1857.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-purchase] Konstantin's letter was shown to his brother, Tsar Alexander II, who wrote "this idea is worth considering" on the front page.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-purchase] Supporters of Konstantin's proposal to immediately withdraw from North America included Admiral Yevfimy Putyatin and the Russian minister to the United States, Eduard de Stoeckl.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-purchase] Gorchakov agreed with the necessity of abandoning Russian America but argued for a gradual process leading to its sale.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-purchase] He found a supporter in the naval minister and former chief manager of the Russian-American Company, Ferdinand von Wrangel.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-purchase] Wrangel pressed for some proceeds to be invested in the economic development of Kamchatka and the Amur Basin.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-purchase] The Emperor eventually sided with Gorchakov, deciding to postpone negotiations until the end of the RAC's patent, set to expire in 1861.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-purchase] Over the winter of 1859–1860, Stoeckl held meetings with United States officials, though he had been instructed not to initiate discussions about the sale of the RAC assets.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-purchase] Communicating primarily with Assistant Secretary of State John Appleton and California senator William M.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-purchase] Gwin, Stoeckl reported the interest expressed by the Americans in acquiring Russian America.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-purchase] While President James Buchanan kept these hearings informal, preparations were made for further negotiations.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-purchase] Stoeckl reported a conversation in which he asked "in passing" what price the U.S. government might pay for the Russian colony and Senator Gwin replied that they "might go as far as $5,000,000", a figure Gorchakov found far too low.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-purchase] Stoeckl informed Appleton and Gwin of this, the latter saying that his Congressional colleagues in Oregon and California would support a larger figure.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-purchase] Buchanan's increasingly unpopular presidency forced the matter to be shelved until a new presidential election.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-purchase] With the oncoming American Civil War, Stoeckl proposed a renewal of the RAC's charter.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-purchase] Two of its ports were to be open to foreign traders and commercial agreements with Peru and Chile to be signed to give "a fresh jolt" to the company.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-purchase] Russia continued to see an opportunity to weaken British power by causing British Columbia, including the Royal Navy base at Esquimalt, to be surrounded or annexed by American territory.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-purchase] Following the Union victory in the Civil War in 1865, the Tsar instructed Stoeckl to re-enter into negotiations with William H.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-purchase] President Andrew Johnson was busy with negotiations about Reconstruction, and Seward had alienated a number of Republicans, so both men believed that the purchase would help divert attention from domestic issues.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-purchase] The negotiations concluded after an all-night session with the signing of the treaty at 04:00 on March 30, 1867.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-purchase] The purchase price was set at $7.2 million (equivalent to $132 million in 2024), or about 2 cents per acre ($4.74/km2).
[src:alaska-day/alaska-purchase] Much of the money Russia earned from the sale was reportedly paid to two Americans, Thomas and William Winans from Baltimore, Maryland, who were under contract with the Tsar to build and maintain Russia's railway system.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-purchase] The Winans were seen as "the robber of the Russian Treasury", contract costs had ballooned exponentially.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-purchase] The Winans received six and a half million rubles of the Alaskan sale proceeds.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-purchase] The Russian name for the Alaska Peninsula was *Alyaska* ("Аляска") or *Alyeska*, from an Aleut word, *alashka* or *alaesksu*, meaning "great land" or "mainland".
[src:alaska-day/alaska-purchase] The United States chose the name "Alaska" to refer to the area purchased from Russia.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-purchase] Seward told the nation that, according to Russian estimates, Alaska had about 60,000 inhabitants.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-purchase] This included about 10,500 who were under the direct government of the Russian fur company: about 8,000 indigenous people and 2,500 people of Russian or mixed Russian and indigenous descent (for example, having a Russian father and a native mother).
[src:alaska-day/alaska-purchase] The remaining 50,000 or so were Inuit or Alaska Natives living outside of Russia's jurisdiction.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-purchase] Seward also said that the Russians were settled at 23 trading posts, placed on accessible islands and at points along the coast.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-purchase] At smaller trading posts, typically only four or five Russians were stationed: their job was to collect furs from the natives for storage and then for shipment when the company's boats arrived to take the furs away.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-purchase] One was New Archangel (now named Sitka), established in 1804 to handle the valuable trade in the skins of sea otters; in 1867, it had 116 small log cabins and 968 residents.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-purchase] Paul, in the Pribilof Islands, which had 100 homes and 283 residents, and was the center of the seal fur industry.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-purchase] Seward and many other Americans expected that Asia would become an important market for U.S. products, and that Alaska would serve as a base for American trade with Asia and globally, and for the extension of American power into the Pacific.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-purchase] Senator Charles Sumner, chair of the Senate Foreign Relations Committee, sponsored the Senate bill authorizing the U.S. to approve the treaty to acquire the territory.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-purchase] He not only agreed about the benefit to trade, but also said he expected the territory to be valuable on its own; having studied the records of explorers, he believed it contained valuable animals and forests.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-purchase] He compared the acquisition to contemporary European colonial acquisitions, such as the French conquest of Algeria.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-purchase] The United States Senate approved the treaty by a vote of 37 to 2.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-purchase] Many Americans believed in 1867 that the purchase process had been corrupt, but W.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-purchase] Dall in 1872 wrote that "there can be no doubt that the feelings of a majority of the citizens of the United States are in favor of it." The notion that the purchase was unpopular among Americans is, a scholar wrote 120 years later, "one of the strongest historical myths in American history.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-purchase] It persists despite conclusive evidence to the contrary, and the efforts of the best historians to dispel it", likely in part because it fits American and Alaskan writers' view of the territory as distinct and filled with self-reliant pioneers.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-purchase] A majority of newspapers either supported the purchase or were neutral.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-purchase] A review of dozens of contemporary newspapers found general support for the purchase, especially in California; most of 48 major newspapers supported the purchase.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-purchase] Public opinion was not universally positive; to some the purchase was known as "Seward's folly", "Walrussia", or "Seward's icebox".
[src:alaska-day/alaska-purchase] Editorials contended that taxpayer money had been wasted on a "polar bear garden".
[src:alaska-day/alaska-purchase] Forty-five percent of supportive newspapers cited the increased potential for annexing British Columbia in their support, and *The New York Times* stated that, consistent with Seward's reason, Alaska would increase American trade with East Asia.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-purchase] The principal urban newspaper that opposed the purchase was the *New York Tribune*, published by Seward opponent Horace Greeley.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-purchase] The ongoing controversy over Reconstruction spread to other acts, including the Alaska purchase.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-purchase] Some opposed the United States obtaining its first non-contiguous territory, seeing it as a colony; others saw no need to pay for land that they expected the country to obtain through manifest destiny.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-purchase] The transfer ceremony took place in Sitka on October 18, 1867.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-purchase] Russian and American soldiers paraded in front of the governor's house; the Russian flag was lowered and the American flag raised amid peals of artillery.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-purchase] A description of the events was published in Finland six years later.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-purchase] After the flag transition was completed, Captain of 2nd Rank Aleksei Alekseyevich Peshchurov said, "General Rousseau, by authority from His Majesty, the Emperor of Russia, I transfer to the United States the territory of Alaska." General Lovell Rousseau accepted the territory.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-purchase] (Peshchurov had been sent to Sitka as commissioner of the Russian government in the transfer of Alaska.) A number of forts, blockhouses and timber buildings were handed over to the Americans.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-purchase] The troops occupied the barracks; General Jefferson C.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-purchase] Davis established his residence in the governor's house, and most of the Russian citizens went home, leaving a few traders and priests who chose to remain.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-purchase] After the transfer, a number of Russian citizens remained in Sitka, but nearly all of them very soon decided to return to Russia, which was still possible at the expense of the Russian-American Company.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-purchase] Moreover, Ahllund's article is the only known description of the return voyage on the *Winged Arrow*, a ship that was specially purchased to transport the Russians back to their native country.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-purchase] "The over-crowded vessel, with crewmen who got roaring drunk at every port, must have made the voyage a memorable one." Ahllund mentions stops at the Sandwich (Hawaiian) Islands, Tahiti, Brazil, London, and finally Kronstadt, the port for St.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-purchase] Petersburg, where they arrived on August 28, 1869.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-purchase] American settlers who shared Sumner's belief in the riches of Alaska rushed to the territory but found that much capital was required to exploit its resources, many of which could also be found closer to markets in the contiguous United States.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-purchase] Most soon left, and by 1873, Sitka's population had declined from about 2,500 to a few hundred.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-purchase] The United States acquired an area over twice as large as Texas, but it was not until the great Klondike Gold Rush in 1896 that Alaska generally came to be seen as a valuable addition to U.S. territory.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-purchase] The seal fishery was one of the chief considerations that induced the United States to purchase Alaska.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-purchase] It provided considerable revenue by the lease of the privilege of taking seals, an amount that was eventually more than the price paid for Alaska.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-purchase] From 1870 to 1890, the seal fisheries yielded 100,000 skins a year.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-purchase] The company to which the administration of the fisheries was entrusted by a lease from the US government paid a rental of $50,000 per annum and in addition thereto $2.62+1⁄2 per skin for the total number taken.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-purchase] The skins were transported to London to be dressed and prepared for world markets.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-purchase] The business grew so large that the earnings of English laborers after the acquisition of Alaska by the United States amounted by 1890 to $12,000,000.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-purchase] However, exclusive US control of this resource was eventually challenged, and the Bering Sea Controversy resulted when the United States seized over 150 sealing ships flying the British flag, based out of the coast of British Columbia.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-purchase] The conflict between the United States and Britain was resolved by an arbitration tribunal in 1893.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-purchase] The waters of the Bering Sea were deemed to be international waters, contrary to the US contention that they were an internal sea.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-purchase] The US was required to make a payment to Britain, and both nations were required to follow regulations developed to preserve the resource.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-purchase] The purchase of Alaska has been referenced as a "bargain basement deal" and as the principal positive accomplishment of the otherwise much-maligned presidency of Andrew Johnson.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-purchase] Barker has argued that the US federal government has not earned a positive financial return on the purchase of Alaska.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-purchase] According to Barker, tax revenue and mineral and energy royalties to the federal government have been less than federal costs of governing Alaska plus interest on the borrowed funds used for the purchase.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-purchase] Miller has taken the argument further by contending that US oil companies that developed Alaskan petroleum resources did not earn enough profits to compensate for the risks that they incurred.
[src:alaska-day/alaska-purchase] Alaska Day is a holiday for all state workers.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] From the 4th century, feasts commemorating all Christian martyrs were held in various places, on various dates near Easter and Pentecost.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] In the 9th century, some churches in the British Isles began holding the commemoration of all saints on November 1, and in the 9th century this was extended to the whole Catholic Church by Pope Gregory IV.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] In Western Christianity, it is celebrated on November 1 by the Roman Catholic Church as well as by many Protestant Churches, such as the Lutheran, Anglican, and Methodist traditions.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] With respect to its festal ranking, All Saints' Day is a solemnity in Catholicism and a festival in Lutheranism.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] The Eastern Orthodox Church and associated Eastern Catholic and Eastern Lutheran churches celebrate it on the first Sunday after Pentecost.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] The Syro-Malabar Church and the Chaldean Catholic Church, both of which are in communion with Rome, as well as the Church of the East, celebrate All Saints' Day on the first Friday after Easter Sunday.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] In the Coptic Orthodox tradition, All Saints' Day is on Nayrouz, celebrated on September 11.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] The day is the start of the Coptic new year, and of its first month, Thout.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] In the Western Christian practice, the liturgical celebration begins with its first vespers on the evening of October 31, All Hallows' Eve (All Saints' Eve or Hallowe'en), and ends at the compline of November 1.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] It is thus the day before All Souls' Day, which commemorates the faithful departed.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] The use of candles by Christians symbolized the light of Christ and the use of lamps at the tombs of Christian martyrs dates back to the early Christian period.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] In Austria and Germany, godparents gift their godchildren Allerheiligenstriezel (All Saint's Braid) on All Saint's Day, while the practice of souling remains popular in Portugal.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] It is a national holiday in many Christian countries.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] The Christian celebration of All Saints' Day and All Souls' Day stems from a belief that there is a powerful spiritual bond between those in heaven (the "Church triumphant"), the living (the "Church militant"), and the "Church penitent" which includes the faithful departed.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] In Catholic theology, the day commemorates all those who have attained the beatific vision in Heaven.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] As such, individuals throughout the Church Universal are honoured, such as Paul the Apostle, Augustine of Hippo and other saints, varying according to the hagiographic traditions of the Church in question.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] In some traditions, the day is also used to celebrate individuals who have personally led one to faith in Jesus, such as one's grandmother or friend.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] The holiday of All Saints' Day falls on November 1 and is followed by All Souls' Day on November 2.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] It is a Solemnity in the Roman Rite of the Catholic Church, a Festival in the Lutheran Churches, and a Principal Feast of the Anglican Communion.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] From the 4th century, there existed in certain places and at sporadic intervals a feast day to commemorate all Christian martyrs.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] It was held on May 13 in Edessa, the Sunday after Pentecost in Antioch, and the Friday after Easter by the Syrians.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] Maximus of Turin preached annually on the Sunday after Pentecost in honor of all martyrs in what is today northern Italy.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] The Comes of Würzburg, the earliest existing ecclesiastical reading list, dating to the late 6th or early 7th century in what is today Germany, lists the Sunday after Pentecost as *dominica in natale sanctorum* ('Sunday of the Nativity of the Saints').
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] By this time, the commemoration had expanded to include all saints, martyred or not.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] On 13 May 609 or 610, Pope Boniface IV consecrated the Pantheon at Rome to the Blessed Virgin Mary and all the martyrs, ordering an anniversary; the feast of *dedicatio Sanctae Mariae ad Martyres* has been celebrated at Rome ever since.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] It is suggested May 13 was chosen by the Pope and earlier by Christians in Edessa because it was the date of the Roman pagan festival of Lemuria, in which malevolent and restless spirits of the dead were propitiated.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] Some liturgiologists suggest that Lemuria was the origin of All Saints, based on their identical dates and their similar theme of "all the dead".
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] Pope Gregory III (731–741) dedicated an oratory in Old St.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] Peter's Basilica to the relics "of the holy apostles and of all saints, martyrs and confessors, of all the just made perfect who are at rest throughout the world".
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] Some sources say Gregory III dedicated the oratory on November 1, and this is why the date became All Saints' Day.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] Other sources say Gregory III held a synod to condemn iconoclasm on 1 November 731, but he dedicated the All Saints oratory on Palm Sunday, 12 April 732.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] By 800, there is evidence that churches in Gaelic Ireland and Anglo-Saxon Northumbria were holding a feast commemorating all saints on November 1.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] There was much Gaelic influence on Northumbria and its church during this period.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] Some manuscripts of the Irish *Martyrology of Tallaght* and *Martyrology of Óengus*, which date to this time, have a commemoration of all saints of the world on November 1.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] In 800, Alcuin of Northumbria recommended the November 1st feast to his friend, Arno of Salzburg in Bavaria.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] Alcuin, a member of Charlemagne's court, may have been responsible for introducing this Irish-Northumbrian feast of All Saints in the Frankish Empire.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] Adoption of the November 1st feast might also have been driven by Irish missionaries, and there were Irish clerics and scholars at Charlemagne's court as well.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] James Frazer represents this school of thought by arguing that November 1 was chosen because Samhain was the date of the Celtic festival of the dead.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] Ronald Hutton argues instead that the earliest documentary sources indicate Samhain was a harvest festival with no particular ritual connections to the dead.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] Hutton proposes that November 1 was a Germanic rather than a Celtic idea.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] In 835, Charlemagne's son and successor, Emperor Louis the Pious, made All Saints' Day on November 1, a holy day of obligation throughout the Frankish Empire.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] His decree was issued "at the instance of Pope Gregory IV and with the assent of all the bishops", confirming the November 1st date.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] Sicard of Cremona, a scholar who lived in the 12th and 13th centuries, proposed that Pope Gregory VII (1073–85) suppressed the May 13th date in favour of 1 November.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] By the 12th century, the May 13th feast of All Saints had been deleted from liturgical books.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] The All Saints octave was added by Pope Sixtus IV (1471–84).
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] In the Catholic Church, All Saints' Day is a holy day of obligation.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] It is celebrated through the offering of the Mass and families visit graveyards through the season of Allhallowtide, especially on All Hallow's Eve, All Saints' Day and All Souls' Day.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] In 1955, the All Saints vigil and the octave were suppressed by the Liturgical reforms of Pope Pius XII, though Traditional Catholic communities, such as the Congregation of Mary Immaculate Queen, continue to observe it.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] The festival was retained after the Reformation in the liturgical calendars of the Evangelical-Lutheran Churches.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] In the Lutheran churches, such as the Church of Sweden, it assumes a role of general commemoration of the dead, though a special emphasis is placed on the martyrs for the faith (cf.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] All Saints Day is a public holiday in Evangelical Lutheran countries, such as Sweden and Finland.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] In some Lutheran congregations, its observance is moved to the first Sunday of November.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] In the Lutheran churches, the liturgical color for All Saints Day is white and Mass is offered on All Saints Day.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] The festival honors the saints of Evangelical-Lutheran Christianity, in addition to all those who have died in the Christian faith (the 'faithful departed'), though in certain congregations, the latter is given more emphasis on the following day, All Souls' Day.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] The faithful visit cemeteries to place flowers and candles on the graves of their loved ones, along with cleaning them.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] In the Church of England, mother church of the Anglican Communion, it is a Principal Feast and may be celebrated either on November 1 or on the Sunday between October 30 and November 5.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] It is also celebrated by other Protestants, such as the United Church of Canada and various Methodist connexions.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] Protestants generally commemorate all Christians, living and deceased, on All Saints' Day; if they observe All Saints' Day at all, they use it to remember all Christians both past and present.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] In the United Methodist Church, All Saints' Day is celebrated on the first Sunday in November.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] It is held not only to remember Saints but also members of the local church congregation who have died.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] In some congregations, a candle is lit by the Acolyte as each person's name is called out by the clergy.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] Prayers and responsive readings may accompany the event.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] Being the vigil of All Saints' Day (All Hallows' Day), in many countries, such as Ireland, the United Kingdom, the United States and Canada, Halloween (All Hallows' Eve or All Saints' Eve) is celebrated on October 31.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] Mass for the Vigil of All Saints is held in Christian congregations of the Catholic, Lutheran and Anglican denominations.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] All Hallows' Eve has traditionally been a day of fasting in Western Christianity; Traditional Catholics, Lutherans and Anglicans continue this practice in the present-day.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] Congregations of the Church of England, mother Church of the Anglican Communion, host light parties in their fellowship halls on All Hallows' Eve.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] In the Lutheran, Anglican and Reformed traditions of Christianity, All Hallows' Eve is dually celebrated as Reformation Day.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] During Allhallowtide (especially on All Hallows' Eve, All Saints' Day and All Souls' Day), it is common for Christians to visit graveyards in order to remember their loved ones; families often pray there and decorate the graves of their loved ones with garlands, flowers, candles as well as incense.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] During the 20th century the observance largely became a secular one, although some traditional Christian groups have continued to embrace the Christian origins of Halloween whereas others have rejected such celebrations.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] In English-speaking countries, services often include the singing of the traditional hymn "For All the Saints" by Walsham How.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] The most familiar tune for this hymn is *Sine Nomine* by Ralph Vaughan Williams.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] Other hymns that are popularly sung during corporate worship on this day are "I Sing a Song of the Saints of God" and "Ye Watchers and Ye Holy Ones".
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] The Eastern Orthodox Church, following the Byzantine tradition, commemorates all saints collectively on the Sunday after Pentecost, **All Saints' Sunday** (Greek: Ἁγίων Πάντων, *Agiōn Pantōn*).
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] By 411, the East Syrians kept the Chaldean Calendar with a "Commemoratio Confessorum" celebrated on the Friday after Easter.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] John Chrysostom from the late 4th or early 5th century marks the observance of a feast of all the martyrs on the first Sunday after Pentecost.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] Some scholars place the location where this sermon was delivered as Constantinople.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] The Feast of All Saints achieved greater prominence in the 9th century, in the reign of the Byzantine Emperor Leo VI "the Wise" (866–911).
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] His wife, Empress Theophano lived a devout life and, after her death, miracles occurred.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] Her husband built a church for her relics and intended to name it to her.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] He was discouraged to do so by local bishops and instead dedicated it to "All Saints".
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] According to tradition, it was Leo who expanded the feast from a commemoration of All Martyrs to a general commemoration of All Saints, whether martyrs or not.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] This Sunday marks the close of the Paschal season.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] To the normal Sunday services are added special scriptural readings and hymns to all the saints (known and unknown) from the Pentecostarion.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] In the late spring, the Sunday following Pentecost Saturday (50 days after Easter) is set aside as a commemoration of all locally venerated saints, such as "All Saints of America", "All Saints of Mount Athos", etc.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] The third Sunday after Pentecost may be observed for even more localised saints, such as "All Saints of St.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] Petersburg", or for saints of a particular type, such as "New Martyrs of the Turkish Yoke".
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] In addition to the Mondays mentioned above, Saturdays throughout the year are days for general commemoration of all saints, and special hymns to all saints are chanted from the Octoechos.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] The celebration of November 1 in Lebanon as a holiday reflects the influence of Western Catholic orders present in Lebanon and is not Maronite in origin.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] The traditional Maronite feast equivalent to the honor of all saints in their liturgical calendar is one of three Sundays in preparation for Lent called the Sunday of the Righteous and the Just.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] The following Sunday is the Sunday of the Faithful Departed (similar to All Souls' Day in Western calendar).
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] In East Syriac tradition the All Saints' Day celebration falls on the first Friday after resurrection Sunday.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] This is because all departed faithful are saved by the blood of Jesus and they resurrected with the Christ.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] Normally in east Syriac liturgy the departed souls are remembered on Friday.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] Church celebrates All Souls' Day on Friday before the beginning of Great lent or Great Fast.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] In Austria and Bavaria, it is customary on All Saints' Day for godfathers to give their godchildren *Allerheiligenstriezel*, a braided yeast pastry.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] People decorate and visit graves of their family members.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] In Belgium, *Toussaint* or *Allerheiligen* is a public holiday.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] Belgians visit the cemeteries to place chrysanthemums on the graves of deceased relatives on All Saints' Day, since All Souls' Day is not a holiday.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] All Saints' Day (Croatian: *Svi sveti*) is observed in Croatia by placing candles and flowers on the graves of the deceased.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] It is a public holiday with most businesses closed.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] Cities provide free public transportation to the local cemeteries.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] Liturgies are also conducted by priests around a central location in some cemeteries; the one held in Mirogoj, Zagreb is broadcast every year on national television.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] In France, and throughout the Francophone world, the day is known as *La Toussaint*.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] Flowers (especially chrysanthemums), or wreaths called *couronnes de toussaints*, are placed at each tomb or grave.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] The following day, November 2 (All Souls' Day) is called *Le jour des morts*, the Day of the Dead.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] In Germany, *Allerheiligen* is a public holiday in five federal states, namely Baden-Württemberg, Bayern, Rheinland-Pfalz, Nordrhein-Westfalen and Saarland.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] They categorize it as a silent day *(stiller Tag)* when public entertainment events are only permitted if the serious character of the day is preserved.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] In Hungary, *Mindenszentek napja* (literally All Saints Day) is a national holiday which is followed by *Halottak napja* (Day of the Dead).
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] On Day of the Dead people take candles and flowers (especially chrysanthemums) on the tombs or graves of all their loved ones and relatives thus many people travel around the country to distant cemeteries.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] People who cannot travel may lay their flowers or candles at the main calvary cross of a nearby cemetery.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] Since only All Saints' Day is a national holiday, most people use this day to visit cemeteries and pay tribute to their deceased relatives.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] As in the case with every national holiday in Hungary if All Saints' Day happens to be a Tuesday or a Thursday then that week's Monday or Friday is observed as a Saturday, making that weekend four days long, and one of the previous or following Saturdays is changed to a workday.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] Traffic in and around cemeteries are much higher than usual on these days with actual police presence.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] In Poland, *Dzień Wszystkich Świętych* is a public holiday.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] Families try to gather together for both All Saints' Day and the All Souls' Day *(Zaduszki)*, the official day to commemorate the departed faithful.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] The celebrations begin with tending to family graves and the surrounding graveyards, lighting candles and leaving flowers.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] November 1 is a public holiday in Poland, while the following All Souls' Day is not.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] The Zaduszki custom of honouring the dead thus corresponds with All Souls' Day celebrations and is much more observed in Poland than in most other places in the West.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] In Portugal, *Dia de Todos os Santos* is a national holiday.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] Families remember their dead with religious observances and visits to the cemetery.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] Portuguese children celebrate the *Pão-por-Deus* tradition (also called *bolinho*, *santorinho*, or *fiéis de Deus*) going door-to-door, (very much like Trick-or-treating) where they receive cakes, nuts, dried fruits, sweets and candies.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] In Spain, el *Día de Todos los Santos* is a national holiday.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] People take flowers to the graves of dead relatives.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] The play *Don Juan Tenorio* is traditionally performed.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] In Lutheran Sweden, the faithful attend Mass on All Saints Day, in addition to visiting cemeteries to clean the graves of their loves ones, while placing flowers and candles on them.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] All Saints' Day is a public holiday or 'silent day' in some cantons of Switzerland.It is marked by bringing flowers and lighting candles in cemeteries, attending church services, baking special breads and pastries like Allerheiligenstriezel, Allerheiligenwecken, Allerheiligenzopf, or (Seelen)zopf.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] Originally, these breads were for children and the poor who said a prayer for the dead.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] In Guatemala, All Saints' Day is a national holiday.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] On that day Guatemalans make a special meal called *fiambre* which is made of cold meats and vegetables; it is customary to visit cemeteries and to leave some of the *fiambre* for their dead.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] It is also customary to fly kites to help unite the dead with the living.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] There are festivals in towns like Santiago Sacatepéquez and Sumpango, where giant colorful kites are flown.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] All Saints' Day in Mexico coincides with the first day of the Day of the Dead (*Día de Muertos*) celebration.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] It commemorates children who have died (*Dia de los Inocentes*), and the second day celebrates all deceased adults.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] Filipinos traditionally observe this day by visiting their families' graves to clean and repair the tombs.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] Prayers for the dead are recited, while offerings are made, the most common being flowers, candles, food, and for Chinese Filipinos, incense and *kim*.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] Many also spend the day and ensuing night holding reunions at the graves with feasting and merriment.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] Though Halloween is usually seen as an American influence, the country's trick-or-treat traditions during Undas are actually much older.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] This tradition was derived from the pre-colonial tradition of *pangangaluluwa*.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] From *káluluwâ* ('spirit double'), it was a practice of early Filipinos, swathed in blankets, going from house to house, and singing as they pretended to be the spirits of ancestors.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] If the owner of the house failed to give *biko* or rice cakes to the *nangángalúluwâ*, the "spirits" would play tricks (such as stealing slippers or other objects left outside the house, or run off with the family's chickens).
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] Pangángaluluwâ practices are still seen in some rural areas.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] During Undas, families visit the graves of loved ones.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] It is believed that by going to the cemetery and offering food, candles, flowers, and sometimes incense, the spirits are remembered and appeased.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] Contrary to common belief, this visitation practice is not an imported tradition.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] Prior to the use of coffins, pre-colonial Filipinos were already visiting burial caves throughout the archipelago as confirmed by research conducted by the University of the Philippines.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] The tradition of *atang* or *hain* is also practiced, where food and other offerings are placed at the gravesite.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] If the family cannot visit, a specific area in the house is set aside for ritual offerings.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] The present date of Undas, November 1, is not a pre-colonial observance but an import from Mexico, where it is known as the Day of the Dead.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] Pre-colonial Filipinos preferred going to the burial caves of the departed occasionally as they believed that *aswáng* (monster, half-vampire, half-werewolf beings) would take the corpse of the dead if it was not properly guarded.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] Watching over the body of the dead is called "paglalamay".
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] However, in some communities, this paglalamay tradition is non-existent and is replaced by other pre-colonial traditions unique to each community.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] Undas is also seen as a family holiday, where members living elsewhere return to their hometowns to visit ancestral graves.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] Family members are expected to remain beside the grave for the entire day and socialize with each other to strengthen ties.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] In some cases, family members going to graves may exceed one hundred people.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] Fighting in any form is taboo during Undas.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] Children are allowed to play with melted candles left at tombs, which they form into wax balls.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] The round balls symbolize the affirmation that everything goes back to where it began, as the living will return to dust whence it came.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] In some cases, families also light candles by the front door, their number equivalent to the number of departed loved ones.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] It is believed that the lights aid the spirits and guide them to the afterlife.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] In Belgium, all Sundays are public holidays; should All Saints' Day fall on a Sunday, then a replacement day on a weekday of choice is given.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] In Monaco, if it falls on a Sunday, the next day is a statutory holiday.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] In Finland, Estonia and Sweden, an All Saints public holiday falls on the Saturday during the period between October 31 and November 6.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] The preceding Friday is a half-holiday in Sweden.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] In Montenegro, All Saints' Day is considered a Catholic holiday and is a non-working day for that religious community.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] In Bosnia and Herzegovina it is a public holiday in the Federation of Bosnia and Herzegovina only.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] In Germany All Saints' is a designated quiet day in states of Baden-Württemberg, Bavaria, North Rhine-Westphalia, Rhineland-Palatinate and Saarland.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] Similarly in Switzerland the following 15 out of 26 cantons have All Saints as a public holiday: Aargau, Appenzell Innerrhoden, Fribourg (partly), Glarus, Jura, Luzern, Nidwalden, Obwalden, Saint Gallen, Solothurn, Schwyz, Ticino, Uri, Valais, and Zug.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] Although the European Commission does not set public holidays for its member states, November 1 is a public holiday for the employees of the institutions of the European Union.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] In the Philippines, where there are two types of public holidays, All Saints' Day is a fixed date, special holiday.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] In India, All Saints' Day is considered a public holiday in the state of Karnataka and a Christian religious holiday throughout the country, which means it is often a common addition to the list of paid holidays at the discretion of the employer, for those that wish to observe.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] In Bolivia, All Saints is a public holiday on November 2, unlike most other countries which celebrate All Souls' Day on that date.
[src:alaska-day/all-saints-day] In Antigua and Barbuda, November 1 falls on Independence Day, in Algeria on Revolution Day and in the US Virgin Islands on Liberty Day.
[src:alaska-day/american-family-day] Arizona resident, John Makkai, is credited with pushing the holiday through the Arizona legislature.
[src:alaska-day/american-family-day] American Family Day began as a 1-year proclamation, signed by then Governor Raúl Héctor Castro, declaring August 7, 1977 American Family Day.
[src:alaska-day/american-family-day] The following year, American Family Day was signed into law as an official Arizona holiday by Governor Bruce Babbitt.
[src:alaska-day/american-family-day] The holiday also caught on in several other states, including North Carolina and Georgia.
